{"title_page": "Sport in Russia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Culture of Russia}}\nThe most popular '''[[sport]]''' '''in [[Russia]]''' is [[Association Football|football]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-FzBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT259&lpg=PT259&dq=what+is+the+most+popular+sport+in+russia+football&source=bl&ots=qh_UYRXhGV&sig=-wK3_012ZO-iNnxaSGeZbiSZvL0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSvOWJnPPMAhWGyoMKHVL0AtU4ChDoAQgsMAY|title=Lonely Planet Russia|first1=Lonely|last1=Planet|first2=Simon|last2=Richmond|first3=Marc|last3=Bennetts|first4=Marc Di|last4=Duca|first5=Anthony|last5=Haywood|first6=Anna|last6=Kaminski|first7=Tom|last7=Masters|first8=Tamara|last8=Sheward|first9=Regis St|last9=Louis|first10=Mara|last10=Vorhees|date=1 February 2015|publisher=Lonely Planet|accessdate=16 December 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> According to [[Yandex]] search analysis results rating of the most popular sports among Russians: \"[[Association Football|Football]] topped the list of the most popular sports in Russia\" with 5 to 10 million requests. [[Ice hockey]] came in second with [[handball]], [[basketball]], [[boxing]], [[auto racing]], [[volleyball]], [[Sport of athletics|athletics]], [[tennis]] and chess rounding out the top ten rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://polit.ru/news/2013/07/17/sport/|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Other popular sports include [[bandy]], [[biathlon]], [[figure skating]], [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifting]], [[gymnastics]], [[wrestling]], [[martial arts]], [[rugby union]], and [[skiing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://www.rusbandy.ru/news/7591|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Soviet Union]] (USSR) competed in the [[Olympic Games]] for the first time at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]]. Soviet and later Russian athletes never finished below fourth place in the number of gold and total medals collected at the Summer Olympics in which they competed. Russia has the most medals stripped for doping violations (51), the most of any country, four times the number of the runner-up, and nearly a third of the global total. The [[Russia at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Russian team]] was partially banned from the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Olympics]] and [[2018 Winter Olympics]] due to the [[Doping in Russia|state-sponsored doping scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=With one year until 2018 Winter Games, Russia's status murky|url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/18647088/with-one-year-2018-winter-games-pyeongchang-russia-status-murky-wake-doping-scandal|website=Espn.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|date=9 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-suspends-russian-noc-and-creates-a-path-for-clean-individual-athletes-to-compete-in-pyeongchang-2018-under-the-olympic-flag|title=IOC suspends Russian NOC and creates a path for clean individual athletes to compete in PyeongChang 2018 under the Olympic Flag|date=5 December 2017|website=Olympic.org|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Russian athletes were allowed to participate at the 2018 Olympics under a [[Olympic Athletes from Russia at the 2018 Winter Olympics|neutral flag]] with a name \"Olympic Athletes from Russia\".\n\n[[File:RIAN archive 833469 6th International Maxi-Marathon of Nuclear Workers.jpg|right|250px|thumb|The 6th International Maxi-Marathon of Nuclear Workers on [[Moscow]]'s central Vasilyevsky Spusk Square, 2001. Participants are workers from 14 countries having [[nuclear power]] plants in their territories.]]\n\n==Football==\n[[File:RussianBear.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Russian football fans with a gigantic \"Go Russia!\" banner, featuring the [[Russian Bear]] on the background of the [[Russian flag]]]]\n{{See also|Football in Russia|2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n\n[[association football|Football]] is the number one sport in the country.<ref name=\"Murdico2005\">{{cite book|author=Suzanne J. Murdico|title=Russia: A Primary Source Cultural Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zwEWwYhv9ZUC&pg=PT96|accessdate=19 November 2013|year=2005|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-2913-6|pages=96\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Dzhusoity | first =Afsati | last2 =Kuznetsov | first2 =Petr | title =Russian soccer loses Abramovich's funding | newspaper =Russia Beyond the Headlines | publisher =Rossiyskaya Gazeta | date =30 August 2013 | url =http://rbth.co.uk/arts/sport/2013/08/30/russian_soccer_loses_abramovichs_funding_29361.html | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Brown | first =Des | title =Russia's Soccer Relationship With England | newspaper =The Moscow Times | publisher =The Moscow Times | date =15 October 2013 | url =http://www.themoscowtimes.com/arts_n_ideas/article/russias-soccer-relationship-with-england/487832.html | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Smith | first =Chris | title =Russia \u2013 A developing football nation | work = Total Football Magazine | publisher =Total Football Magazine | url =http://www.totalfootballmag.com/features/world-football/russia-a-developing-football-nation/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> A high proportion of men are interested in it to a certain extent (and many children play it regularly) and women also join men when it comes to the national team. The Russian league has a fairly high degree of competitiveness. Many notable talented foreign players have been and are playing in the Russian league as well as local talented players worthy of a spot in the starting eleven of the best clubs.<ref>{{Citation | last =Nsehe | first =Mfonobong | title =Soccer Star Samuel Eto'o To Earn $25 Million With Russian Team | work =Forbes | publisher =Forbes.com LLC | date =12 August 2011 | url =https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2011/08/12/soccer-star-samuel-etoo-to-earn-25-million-with-russian-team/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title =Russia cracks down on hooligans | work =Fox Sports | publisher =Fox Sports Australia Pty Limited | date =22 June 2013 | url =http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/russia-cracks-down-on-hooligans/story-e6frf423-1226667892531 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Murphy | first =Chris | title =World Cup: Russian racism furore is the latest headache for FIFA | newspaper =CNN | publisher =Cable News Network | date =25 October 2013 | url =http://edition.cnn.com/2013/10/25/sport/football/football-russia-racism-2018-world-cup-fifa/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nRussia was awarded the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] on the 2nd of December 2018, hosting the tournament for the first time.<ref>{{cite news | title =World Cup 2018 host Russia has a serious soccer hooligan problem | newspaper =news.com.au | publisher =News Limited | date =31 October 2013 | url =http://www.news.com.au/world/world-cup-2018-host-russia-has-a-serious-soccer-hooligan-problem/story-fndir2ev-1226750850902 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Williams | first =Carol J. | title =Soccer World Cup 2018 host is asked to explain anti-gay law | newspaper =Los Angeles Times  | publisher =Tribune Company | date =14 August 2013 | url =http://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-soccer-2018-host-russia-gay-law-20130814,0,4543633.story#axzz2l6HVegLj | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Bird | first =Liviu | title =Russia's racism stems from lack of education but can be reversed, experts say | work =NBC Sports: ProSoccerTalk | publisher =NBC Sports | date =31 October 2013 | url =http://prosoccertalk.nbcsports.com/2013/10/31/russias-racism-stems-from-lack-of-education-but-can-be-reversed-experts-say/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> The event took place from 14 June to 15 July 2018, in which the [[Russia national football team|Russian team]] had its best performance since the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 tournament]], reaching the quarter-finals for the first time since the breakup of the Soviet Union, where they lost to eventual finalists [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/08/russia-world-cup-exit-proud-croatia-penalties|title=Blood, sweat and beers: Russia down but proud after World Cup exit|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=2018-07-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n[[Beach soccer]] is a popular sport in Russia since its International Growth in the late 1990s and with the establishment of the [[FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup]] by the national teams of the member associations of [[FIFA]]. Russia is amongst the most successful and dominant country of the sport,{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} along with [[Brazil]], [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]].\n\n==Ice hockey==\n{{See also|Ice hockey in Russia|Russia men's national ice hockey team|}}\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev 20 May 2008-2.jpg|right|220px|thumb|President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] meets with the 2008 national hockey team.]]\n\nThe [[Kontinental Hockey League]] (KHL) is mostly made up of Russian teams and is widely considered the second best league in the world, after the [[NHL]]. Russian teams have won every KHL championship.\n\nRussia has won the World Championships several times:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Location !! Result\n|-\n| [[1993 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1993]] || [[Dortmund]] / [[Munich]], {{ih|GER}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2008 IIHF World Championship|2008]] || [[Quebec City]] / [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], {{ih|CAN}} ||bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2009 IIHF World Championship|2009]] || [[Bern]] / [[Kloten]], {{ih|SUI}} ||bgcolor=gold| '''Gold'''\n|-\n| [[2012 IIHF World Championship|2012]] || [[Helsinki]], {{ih|FIN}} / [[Stockholm]], {{ih|SWE}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2014 IIHF World Championship|2014]] || [[Minsk]], {{ih|BLR}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n|}\n\n==Volleyball==\n[[File:Paris Volley - Lokomotiv Belgorod, CEV Champions League, 6 November 2014 - 04.JPG|right|210px|thumb|[[Sergey Tetyukhin]], the most successful veteran professional player, celebrated his 40th birthday in 2015, and is still a member of Russia's National team.]]\n* Gold medals (2002, 2011, 2013),5 silver medals (1993, 1998, 2000, 2007, 2010), 6 bronze medals (1997, 1997, 2001, 2006, 2008, 2009)\n\nThe [[Russia women's national volleyball team|Russian women's national volleyball team]] is ranked fifth in the [[FIVB World Rankings]].\n\nRecord for achievements of the Russian women's volleyball team:\n* 2 Olympic silver medals (2000 and 2004)\n* 2 [[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship|FIVB World Championships]] gold medals (2006 and 2010)\n* 1 [[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Champions Cup]] gold medal (1997), 1 silver medal (2001), and 1 bronze medal (1993)\n\nThe Russian volleyball junior team continue to excel, in the [[FIVB]] men ranking for junior and youth, Russia is placed first the men.\n\n==Bandy==\n[[File:2012bandy russia-sweden1.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Russia national bandy team]] in the [[Bandy World Championship 2012|World Championship 2012]]]]\nOne traditionally popular sport is [[bandy]] (informally called \"Russian hockey\"). It is considered a [[national sport]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eng.tatar-inform.ru/news/2011/01/21/33986/|title=Russian bandy players blessed for victory at world championship in Kazan|date=21 January 2011|publisher=Tatar-Inform|accessdate=31 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424230703/http://eng.tatar-inform.ru/news/2011/01/21/33986/|archivedate=24 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and is one of the biggest spectator sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://www.business-gazeta.ru/article/34748/14/&ei=pfRZT6TbIIPprAf569ijDA&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCIQ7gEwAA&prev=/search?q=%25D0%25A5%25D0%25BE%25D0%25BA%25D0%25BA%25D0%25B5%25D0%25B9+%25D1%2581+%25D0%25BC%25D1%258F%25D1%2587%25D0%25BE%25D0%25BC+%25D0%2590%25D0%25B2%25D1%2581%25D1%2582%25D1%2580%25D0%25B0%25D0%25BB%25D0%25B8%25D1%258F+%25D0%25A1%25D0%25BA%25D1%2580%25D1%258B%25D0%25BD%25D0%25BD%25D0%25B8%25D0%25BA&hl=en&biw=1024&bih=634&prmd=imvns|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> According to one survey, it is the third most popular sport in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://www.rusbandy.ru/news/7438/|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Most of the modern rules were written in England by [[Charles Goodman Tebbutt]], but the Russians claim to be the inventors of the game, and indeed there were bandy-like games played in Russia before the modern rules were standardized. When [[Federation of International Bandy]] was founded in 1955, by the [[Soviet Union]] and three Nordic countries, a common set of rules were agreed upon. Mostly the English ruled prevailed. However, one important exception was the boards from the Soviet rules.\n\nThe [[Soviet Union national bandy team|Soviet national team]] won all the [[Bandy World Championship]]s from the start 1957 until 1979. Russia is almost always one of the two best and has never missed out on a medal. The attendance has decreased in the last few years. It's still one of the biggest spectator sports though. After 10 rounds of the 2011\u20132012 [[Russian Bandy League]] the average attendance was 3,887.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://bandynet.ru/node/23247&ei=XEPhTpSGEYzMtAaihc3yAw&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ7gEwAA&prev=/search?q=http://bandynet.ru/node/23247&hl=en&biw=1024&bih=677&prmd=imvns|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The club with biggest public support is [[Kuzbass Kemerovo Bandy Club|HC Kuzbass]] from [[Kemerovo]]. About 26,000 watched the opening game against [[Dynamo Moscow (bandy club)|Dynamo Moscow]]. [[Yenisey Bandy Club|Yenisey]] is the current (2015) champion of the domestic league.\n\n[[Russia women's national bandy team|The national team for women]] took the silver medal in the six first [[Women's Bandy World Championship|World Championships]]. In [[2014 Women's Bandy World Championship|the 2014 WCS]], the first gold medal came.\n\nBandy is the only sport to enjoy the patronage of the [[Russian Orthodox Church]] since they're very interested in strengthening their national traditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://bandynet.ru/v1/node/15183&sandbox=1|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBandy is a team winter sport played on ice, in which skaters use sticks to direct a ball into the opposing team's goal. The rules of the game have many similarities to those of association football. The game is played on a rectangle of ice, the same size as a football field. Each team has eleven players, one of whom is the goalkeeper. A standard bandy match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each. The offside rule is also similar to that observed in football.\n\n== Biathlon ==\n[[Biathlon]] is the most popular winter sport in Russia and ranking 1st in overall polls and TV viewership for the winter seasons. [[Russia]] has had many successful biathletes and has won Olympic and World medals. Notable biathletes include [[Vladimir Melanin]], [[Nikolay Kruglov]], [[Alexander Tikhonov]], [[Valeriy Medvedtsev]], [[Venera Chernyshova]], [[Elena Golovina]] and [[Svetlana Petcherskaia]] during the Soviet era and [[Vladimir Drachev]], [[Pavel Rostovtsev]], [[Maxim Tchoudov]], [[Viktor Maigourov]], [[Olga Zaitseva]] and [[Anton Shipulin]] in the post-communist era.\n\n==Figure skating==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin visited the Iceberg Skating Palace (2014-02-09) 04.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Russian figure skating team at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]]]] [[Figure skating]] is another popular sport; in the 1960s the Soviet Union rose to become a dominant power in figure skating, especially in pairs skating and ice dancing. At every Winter Olympics from 1964 through 2006, a Soviet or Russian pair won gold, often considered the longest winning streak in modern sports history. The streak ended in 2010 when a Chinese pair won gold in [[Figure skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Winter Olympics]], a Russian pair returned to winning gold in pairs at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. Even after the fall of the [[Soviet Union]], Russia still produced multiple Olympic and World Champions in figure skating notably [[Alexei Urmanov]], [[Ilia Kulik]], [[Alexei Yagudin]], [[Evgeni Plushenko]], [[Maria Butyrskaya]], [[Irina Slutskaya]], [[Adelina Sotnikova]], [[Yulia Lipnitskaya]], [[Maya Usova]], [[Alexander Zhulin]], [[Oksana Grishuk]], [[Evgeni Platov]], [[Anjelika Krylova]], [[Oleg Ovsyannikov]], [[Tatiana Navka]], [[Roman Kostomarov]], [[Ekaterina Gordeeva]], [[Sergei Grinkov]], [[Natalia Mishkutenok]], [[Artur Dmitriev]], [[Tatiana Totmianina]], [[Maxim Marinin]], [[Elena Berezhnaya]], [[Anton Sikhuralidze]], [[Tatiana Volosozhar]], [[Maxim Trankov]], [[Ksenia Stolbova]], [[Fedor Klimov]], [[Elena Ilinykh]], [[Nikita Katsalapov]], [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]], [[Evgenia Medvedeva]], [[Elena Radionova]].\n\nThe [[Russian Figure Skating Championships]] are a figure skating national championship held annually to determine the national champions of Russia. Skaters compete at the senior level in the disciplines of men's singles, women's singles, pair skating, and ice dancing.\nThe first Russian national competition was held on 5 March 1878 in St. Petersburg, Russian Empire. The winner was V. I. Sreznevski. From 1897\u2013present, official Russian national championships in figure skating were held. The first national champion of Russia in figure skating was Alexandr Nikitich Panshin, who won the Russian nationals from 1897 to 1900.\n\nBetween 1924 and 1990 Russian national championships in figure skating were not held. During this time, Russian skaters competed at the [[Soviet Figure Skating Championships]].\n\n== Speed skating ==\n\n=== Long track speed skating ===\n[[File:WSDSSC Kolomna 2016 - Pavel Kulizhnikov 2.JPG|left|thumb|300px|[[Pavel Kulizhnikov]]]]\nSpeed skating has a long tradition of excellence since the Russian Empire with [[Nikolay Strunnikov]] being one of the pioneers in speed skating, then in the [[Soviet Union]] with Speed Skating greats [[Lidiya Skoblikova]], [[Maria Isakova]], [[Valentina Stenina|the Stenins]], [[Pavel Pegov]], [[Lyudmila Titova]], [[Sergey Khlebnikov]], [[Yuri Mikhaylov]], [[Natalya Petrusyova]], [[Oleg Goncharenko]], [[Inga Artamonova]], [[Pavel Pegov]], [[Tamara Rylova]], [[Nina Statkevich]], [[Nikolay Gulyayev]], [[Igor Malkov]], [[Galina Stepanskaya]], [[Boris Shilkov]], [[Tatyana Averina]], [[Viktor Kosichkin]], [[Klara Guseva]], [[Valery Muratov]], [[Sergey Marchuk]], [[Maria Isakova]], [[Oleg Bozhev]], [[Yevgeny Grishin (speed skater)|Yevgeny Grishin]], [[Yevgeny Kulikov]]. Even after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]], the [[Russian Federation]] has maintained success in Speed Skating with [[Svetlana Bazhanova]], [[Aleksandr Golubev (speed skater)|Aleksandr Golubev]], [[Yevgeny Lalenkov]], [[Svetlana Zhurova]], [[Dmitry Lobkov]], [[Dmitry Dorofeyev]], [[Sergey Klevchenya]], [[Olga Fatkulina]], [[Ivan Skobrev]], [[Olga Graf]], [[Aleksey Yesin]]. Among the new generation of Russian talents in Speed Skating taking the World Championships and World Cup titles include [[Natalya Voronina]], [[Denis Yuskov]], [[Pavel Kulizhnikov]], [[Elizaveta Kazelina]], and [[Ruslan Murashov]].\n\n=== Short track speed skating ===\nAlthough short track is not as popular as long track in terms of results and history of winning tradition in Russia. It saw a major boost in popularity after the [[2014 Sochi Olympics]] with Korean born [[Viktor Ahn]] who competed for Russia winning three gold medals in Sochi. Other successful athletes at the Olympics and doing well in the World Championships and World Cup competitions are local born speed skaters [[Semion Elistratov]], [[Vladimir Grigorev]], [[Dmitry Migunov]], [[Sofia Prosvirnova]], [[Tatiana Borodulina]] [[Viktoriya Troytskaya]], and [[Ruslan Zakharov]].\n\n==Other winter sports==\nOther winter sports the Soviets or Russia have been strong in are [[bobsleigh]], [[Skeleton (sport)|skeleton]] and [[luge]].\n\n==Basketball==\nBasketball is a popular sport in Russia. The [[Russia national basketball team|Russian national basketball team]] is the heir of the [[Soviet Union national basketball team]] and has won several international titles.\n\nRussia is home to several internationally recognized players such as [[Andrei Kirilenko]], and 2016 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] Champion [[Timofey Mozgov]].\n\n[[PBC CSKA Moscow]] is the second most successful team in the history of European club competitions.\n\n==Rugby union==\n{{Main|Rugby union in Russia}}\n{{See also|Rugby union in the Soviet Union}}\n[[Rugby union]] is a growing sport in [[Russia]]. [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]] is ranked 17th worldwide by the [[International Rugby Board]] (IRB),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irb.com/rankings/full.html|title=Official IRB Rankings|website=Irb.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810042746/http://www.irb.com/rankings/full.html|archivedate=10 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with over one hundred clubs and close to 20,000 players nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000087/index.html|title=Official Russia Playing Numbers|website=Irb.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021032812/http://www.irb.com/unions/union%3D11000087/index.html|archivedate=21 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRussian domestic rugby went professional in 2005 with the launch of the [[Professional Rugby League]]. After a post-Soviet lull, Russian players are again signing with major clubs in England and France.\n\n[[Krasnoyarsk]], a large Siberian city, has traditionally been the stronghold of Russian rugby union. Domestic matches are covered in the local media, and the intra-city derby match between sides Krasny Yar and Enisei-STM can attract large crowds.\n\n[[Rugby football]] in the [[Russian Empire]] pre-dated the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Russian Revolution]] by a number of years, but it was only played sporadically. It appears to have been the first (non-indigenous) football code to be played in Russia, around a decade before the introduction of [[association football]].<ref name=Riordan1>Riordan, James ''Sport in Soviet Society \u2014 development of sport and physical education in Russia and the USSR'' ([[Cambridge University Press]], [[Cambridge]], England, 1977) p22</ref> Mr Hopper, a Scotsman, who worked in Moscow arranged a match in the 1880s; the first football match was in 1892.<ref name=Riordan1/> In 1886, however, the Russian police clamped down on rugby because they considered it \"brutal, and liable to incite demonstrations and riots\"<ref name=Riordan1/> Condemnation by the tsar's police probably deterred many people from playing, and records of rugby over the next thirty years are sparse.\n\nRussia qualified and competed in the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in [[New Zealand]] as Europe 2 after finishing second in the 2008\u201310 ENC. This was the team's debut in the tournament, where they faced [[Australian rugby union team|Australia]], [[Irish rugby union team|Ireland]], [[Italian rugby union team|Italy]] and the [[United States rugby union team|United States]] in Group C of the tournament. Being the second-lowest-ranked team in the tournament, Russia performed comparatively well in their opening match, running the USA close in an encounter which was lost 6\u201313. This was followed by comprehensive losses against Italy (53\u201317), Ireland (62\u201312) and Australia (68\u201322).\n\n==Rugby league==\n{{Main|Rugby league in Russia}}\n\n[[Rugby league]] is a growing sport in [[Russia]]. [[Russia national rugby league team|Russia]] is ranked 16th worldwide by the [[Rugby League International Federation]] (RLIF),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rlif.com/|title=RLIF \u2013 Rugby League International Federation|website=Rlif.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> with over 2,000 participants nationwide.\n\nRussian domestic rugby league is played at youth, student and adult levels.\n\n==Australian rules football==\nThe first Australian rules football clubs in Russia were created in May 2011, with groups starting practice matches in [[Moscow]] and [[Krasnoyarsk]] within a few weeks of each other.  Both fledgling clubs have been started by an expat Australian, but with the remainder of the playing group consisting of local Russians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20110530182212683|title=Russia's 2nd footy club springs up in a month \u2013 World Footy News|website=Worldfootynews.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20110525195432763|title=Plans in motion to create Russia's first footy club \u2013 World Footy News|website=Worldfootynews.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nRussia competed at the 2011 AFL 9s Euro Cup in Belfast, finishing in 10th place (out of 18), with wins over Catalunya and Denmark and losses to Croatia and Wales.\n\nIn 2013 there are five Australian Football clubs playing in a Moscow competition almost exclusively Russians. They are the Bees, Cherkizon, Shooters, Cosmic Pirates and Slava.\n\nIn 2015 St. Petersburg Cats team firstly took part in Gagarin Cup, ANZAC Cup and Concrete and Steel cup.\nIn 2015 May, the ANZAC Day Cup was played for the first time in Saint Petersburg at the Kolomyagi Stadium. The visiting team representing Moscow was the Lazy Koalas. The result was very lopsided, but the fact that a formal game was played outside Australia at all for such an insignificant sport was considered a success.\nScores: Lazy Koalas (Moscow) 921 defeated Saint Petersburg 13 with the game called off at halftime due to a mercy rule taking effect. \nIn 2016 Russian national team took part in AFL Europe Cup in Lisbon\n\n==Tennis==\n[[File:US Open 2012 - Sharapova 03.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Maria Sharapova]] is Russia's most successful tennis athlete. She is also the highest earning female athlete.]]\nSince the end of the Soviet era, [[tennis]] has grown in popularity and Russia has produced a number of famous tennis players. In recent years, the amount of top Russian women players has been considerable, with both [[Maria Sharapova]] and [[Dinara Safina]] reaching number one in the WTA rankings. Other Russian women to achieve international success include [[Elena Dementieva]], [[Ekaterina Makarova]], [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]], [[Anastasia Myskina]], [[Nadia Petrova]], [[Vera Zvonareva]], [[Elena Vesnina]], [[Anna Chakvetadze]], [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]] and [[Anna Kournikova]]. The Russian Federation has won the [[Fed Cup]] 4 times, in [[2004 Fed Cup|2004]], [[2005 Fed Cup|2005]], [[2007 Fed Cup|2007]] and [[2008 Fed Cup|2008]].\n\nAt the [[Tennis at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing Olympics]], Russia swept the women's tennis podium with [[Elena Dementieva]] winning the gold, [[Dinara Safina]] and [[Vera Zvonareva]] the silver and bronze, respectively. As of 16 October 2009, two Russian women were ranked in the WTA tour's top 10; with an additional two in the Top 20.\n\nRussia also boasts two former number 1 men's players\u2014Safina's older brother [[Marat Safin]] and [[Yevgeny Kafelnikov]]. Other Russian men that have made the top 50 include [[Nikolay Davydenko]], [[Igor Andreev]], [[Igor Kunitsyn]], and [[Mikhail Youzhny]]. The Russian men won the [[Davis Cup]] in [[2002 Davis Cup|2002]] and [[2006 Davis Cup|2006]].\n\nAmong Russia's new talents helping to continue the sporting tradition includes, [[Daria Kasatkina]], [[Andrey Kuznetsov (tennis)|Andrey Kuznetsov]], [[Margarita Gasparyan]], [[Andrey Rublev (tennis)|Andrey Rublev]], [[Sofya Zhuk]], and [[Roman Safiullin]].\n\n==Gymnastics==\n\n===Rhythmic gymnastics===\n[[File:Jana Kudrjavceva.jpg|thumb|left|210px|[[Yana Kudryavtseva]]]]\n[[Rhythmic gymnastics]] is considered one of the most popular sports in Russia. In addition, it is considered in general that [[Russia]] has the best rhythmic gymnasts. [[Evgenia Kanaeva]], three-time all around world champion and first and only back to back gold medallist at the olympic games, [[Yulia Barsukova]], [[Irina Tchachina]], [[Galina Beloglazova]], [[Irina Devina]], [[Tatiana Druchinina]], [[Elena Karpuchina]], [[Tatiana Kravtchenko]], [[Galima Shugurova]], [[Oxana Kostina]], [[Alina Kabaeva]], [[Natalia Lipkovskaya]], [[Daria Dmitrieva]], [[Amina Zaripova]], [[Daria Kondakova]], [[Laysan Utiasheva]], [[Zarina Gizikova]], [[Daria Shkurikhina]], [[Vera Sessina]], [[Margarita Mamun]], [[Yelena Posevina]], [[Anastasia Maksimova]], [[Olga Ilina]], [[Anna Gavrilenko]], [[Karolina Sevastyanova]], [[Anastasia Bliznyuk]], [[Alina Makarenko]], [[Ksenia Dudkina]], [[Anastasia Nazarenko]], [[Uliana Donskova]], [[Margarita Aliychuk]], [[Yanina Batyrchina]], [[Tatiana Gorbunova]], [[Maria Titova]], [[Aleksandra Soldatova]], [[Yana Kudryavtseva]], [[Daria Svatkovskaya]], [[Dina Averina]], [[Arina Averina]], [[Veronika Polyakova]], [[Yulia Bravikova]], [[Daria Dubova]], [[Sofya Skomorokh]] and [[Diana Borisova]] are amongst Russia's successful and top rhythmic gymnasts. There are many rhythmic gymnastics clubs in Russia and the most famous one is the Gazprom School which [[Irina Viner]] teaches rhythmic gymnasts in Novogorsk, Moscow, where the Russian National team is also based.\n\n=== Artistic gymnastics ===\n[[File:\u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Svetlana Khorkina]]]]Before the breakup of the [[Soviet Union]] in 1991, Soviet gymnasts dominated both men's and women's gymnastics commencing with the introduction of the full women's program into the Olympics and the overall increased standardization of the Olympic Gymnastics competition format which happened in 1952. From 1952 to 1992 inclusive, the Soviet women's squad won almost every single team title in [[World Gymnastics Championships|World Championship]] competition and at the [[Summer Olympics]]: the only four exceptions were the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Olympics]], which they did not attend, and the 1966, 1979 and 1987 World Championships. Some of the famous Soviet gymnasts were from the [[Russian SFSR]], or of Russian origin born in the former [[Republics of the Soviet Union|SSR]].\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Soviet Union, they competed together as one nation for the last time at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] as a \"Unified Team\" winning the gold. though not as dominant as the [[Soviet Union]] and with the emergence of new countries excelling in gymnastics and having a gymnast apparatus specialist, [[Russia]] has maintained the tradition of gymnastics excellence, medalling at every Worlds and Olympic competition in both MAG and WAG disciplines, except in the [[Gymnastics at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]], where the Russian women team did not win any medals. Notable Russian gymnasts include: [[Svetlana Khorkina]], [[Alexei Nemov]], [[Nikolai Andrianov]], [[Alexander Dityatin]], [[Larissa Latynina]], [[Yelena Shushunova]], [[Elena Zamolodchikova]], [[Natalia Yurchenko]], [[Elena Mukhina]], [[Olga Mostepanova]], [[Yuri Titov]], [[Anton Golotsutskov]], [[Yekaterina Lobaznyuk]], [[Yelena Produnova]], [[Natalia Shaposhnikova]], [[Ludmilla Tourischeva]], [[Anastasia Grishina]], [[Aleksandr Balandin (gymnast)|Aleksandr Balandin]], [[Maria Paseka]], [[Nikolai Kuksenkov]], [[Ksenia Afanasyeva]], [[Aliya Mustafina]], [[Denis Ablyazin]], [[Emin Garibov]], [[Viktoria Komova]], [[David Belyavskiy]], [[Nikita Nagornyy]], [[Maria Kharenkova]], [[Nikita Ignatyev]], [[Daria Spiridonova]], [[Angelina Melnikova]], [[Natalia Kapitonova]], [[Andrei Makolov]], [[Elena Eremina]] and [[Seda Tutkhalyan]].\n\n==Swimming and diving==\n[[File:Swimming pools in Russia.png|thumb|right|300px|Number of [[swimming pool]]s in Russia, 1993\u20132013]]\n[[File:Alexander Popov 006.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Alexander Popov (swimmer)|Alexander Popov]]]]\nSwimming is mostly an elite sport for most Russians, however before the dissolution of the [[USSR]], Swimming was an institutionalized and recreational sport and excelled in the Olympic Games competing against [[East Germany]] in the total swimming medals table. Russia has not achieved the same success as that of the [[Soviet Union]] nevertheless there has still been a few notable Russian swimmers that excelled, [[Alexander Popov (swimmer)|Alexander Popov]], a four-time Olympic gold medalist is regarded as one of the greatest sprint freestyle swimmers of all time,{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} and the only male swimmer in history to win four individual Olympic gold medals in freestyle events. Other Notable Russian swimmers in the 1990s and early 2000s include: [[Denis Pankratov]], [[Yevgeny Sadovyi]], [[Vladimir Pyshnenko]], [[Yury Prilukov]], [[Arkady Vyatchanin]], [[Roman Sludnov]], [[Andrey Grechin]]. After the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], Russia's new elite swimmers have shown improved results.\n\nDiving is also a sport in Russia with a long soviet tradition.\n\nRussia has dominated synchronized swimming at the Olympic Games and World Championships since the [[2000 Sydney Olympics]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} Notable Olympic champions and synchronized swimmers include: [[Anastasia Davydova]], [[Anastasia Ermakova]], [[Natalia Ishchenko]], [[Svetlana Romashina]], [[Darina Valitova]] and [[Aleksandr Maltsev (synchronized swimmer)|Aleksandr Maltsev]].\n\n==Athletics==\n[[File:La russe Elena Isinbaeva m\u00e9daille de bronze olympique du saut \u00e0 la perche \u00e0 Londres.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Russian Pole vaulter [[Yelena Isinbayeva]]]]Russia has maintained strong results particularly in [[High jump]], [[Long jump]], [[Track and field|track athletics]], [[Hurdling]], [[Pole vault]], [[racewalking]], [[Hammer throw]], [[Triple jump]], [[Javelin throw]], [[Heptathlon]]. Some well known Russian athletes include [[Yelena Isinbayeva]], [[Anna Chicherova]], [[Ivan Ukhov]], [[Tatyana Lysenko]], [[Yuliya Zaripova]], [[Natalya Antyukh]], [[Mikhail Ryzhov (athlete)|Mikhail Ryzhov]], [[Andrey Silnov]], [[Aleksandr Ivanov (racewalker)|Aleksandr Ivanov]], [[Ekaterina Koneva]], [[Yelena Slesarenko]], [[Sergey Shubenkov]], [[Mariya Kuchina]], [[Yuriy Borzakovskiy]], [[Darya Klishina]], [[Aleksandr Menkov]], [[Aleksey Fyodorov (athlete)|Aleksey Fyodorov]], [[Elena Lashmanova]], [[Lyukman Adams]], [[Daniil Tsyplakov]], [[Ilya Shkurenyov]].\n\nRussia was banned from the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics|2017]] and [[2019 World Championships in Athletics|2019 World Championships]] because of [[Doping in Russia|state-sponsored doping]].\n\n==Orienteering==\n{{Main|Russian Orienteering Federation}}\n\nThe '''Russian Orienteering Federation''' ([[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041e\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\u0424\u0421\u041e)) is the [[Russia]]n national organisation of [[orienteering]]. It is a full member of the [[International Orienteering Federation]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.orienteering.org/i3/index.php?/iof2006/iof/member_federations/iof_member_federations|title= IOF Member Federations|accessdate= 20 June 2008|work= [[International Orienteering Federation]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080618185711/http://www.orienteering.org/i3/index.php?%2Fiof2006%2Fiof%2Fmember_federations%2Fiof_member_federations|archivedate= 18 June 2008|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Boxing==\n[[File:Alexander Povetkin 2015.png|thumb|right|220px|[[Alexander Povetkin]]]]\n{{See also|Russian fist fighting}}\n\nRussia is a boxing country powerhouse with many world title holders, Olympic champions and legends of the sport. Successful professional and amateur boxers include: [[Alexander Povetkin]], [[Nikolai Valuev]], [[Dmitry Bivol]], [[Eduard Troyanovsky]], [[Aleksei Tishchenko]], [[Kostya Tszyu]], [[Evgeny Tishchenko]], [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]], [[Albert Tumenov]], [[Magomed Abdusalamov]], [[Shamil Sabirov]], [[Oleg Maskaev]], [[Dmitry Kudryashov (boxer)|Dmitry Kudryashov]], [[Boris Kuznetsov (boxer)|Boris Kuznetsov]], [[Aleksandr Lebziak]], [[Sofya Ochigava]], [[Oleg Saitov]], [[Georgy Balakshin]], [[Oleg Grigoryev]], [[Vassily Solomin]], [[Nikolay Korolyov (boxer)|Nikolay Korolyov]], [[Raimkul Malakhbekov]], [[Evgeny Makarenko]], [[Alexander Maletin]], [[Alexei Lezin]], [[Gennady Kovalev]], [[Sergey Kazakov]], [[Matvey Korobov]], [[Sultan Ibragimov]], [[Artur Beterbiyev]], [[Misha Aloyan]], [[Denis Boytsov]], [[Dmitry Chudinov]], [[Fedor Chudinov]], [[Gennadiy Shatkov]], [[Grigory Drozd]], [[Egor Mekhontsev]], [[David Ayrapetyan]], [[Boris Lagutin]], [[Denis Lebedev]], [[Rashid Magomedov]], [[Ruslan Provodnikov]], [[Viktor Rybakov]], [[Vladimir Safronov]], [[Stanislav Stepashkin]], [[Valerian Sokolov]], [[Vasilii Egorov]], [[Vitaly Dunaytsev]],\n\n== Judo ==\nRussia has become a key player in sport of [[Judo]], even under the [[Soviet Union]], it has produced multiple Olympic champions and medalists. The popularity was increased under President [[Vladimir Putin]] promoting the sport, and with Russia producing multiple Olympic and World champions. Notable judokas over the decades include: [[Vladimir Nevzorov]], [[Kamal Khan-Magomedov]], [[Alexander Mikhaylin]], [[Oleg Stepanov]], [[Anatoly Laryukov]], [[Beslan Mudranov]], [[Tamerlan Tmenov]], [[Ivan Nifontov]], [[Arsen Galstyan]], [[Sergei Kosorotov]], [[Mansur Isaev]], [[Nikolai Solodukhin]], [[Elena Ivashchenko]], [[Kirill Denisov]], [[Tagir Khaybulaev]], [[Sergei Kosmynin]], [[Vitali Kuznetsov (judoka)|Vitali Kuznetsov]], [[Natalia Kuziutina]], [[Vitaliy Makarov]], [[Serhiy Novikov (judo fighter)|Serhiy Novikov]], [[Mikhail Pulyaev]], [[Dmitri Sergeyev (judoka)|Dmitri Sergeyev]], [[Yury Styopkin]],\n\n==Martial arts==\n[[File:Fedor Emelianenko 2006.jpg|thumb|left|160px| [[Fedor Emelianenko]]]][[File:Batu Khasikov 2011.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Batu Khasikov]]]]\nMixed martial arts is another popular sport producing many world class international and national fighters.\n\nNotable athletes include: [[Fedor Emelianenko]], [[Batu Khasikov]], [[Oleg Taktarov]], [[Vitaly Minakov]], [[Rasul Mirzaev]], [[Julia Berezikova]], [[Andrey Koreshkov]], [[Vyacheslav Vasilevsky]], [[Sergei Kharitonov]], [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]], [[Vladimir Mineev]], [[Muslim Salikhov]], [[Murad Machaev]], [[Viktor Nemkov]], [[Adlan Amagov]], [[Islam Makhachev]], [[Ramazan Ramazanov]], [[Zubaira Tukhugov]], [[Volk Han]], [[Omari Akhmedov]], [[Sultan Aliev]], [[Vener Galiev]], [[Ali Bagautinov]], [[Alexander Ustinov]], [[Rustam Khabilov]], [[Alexander Sarnavskiy]], [[Ruslan Magomedov]], [[Artem Levin]], [[Alexander Volkov (fighter)|Alexander Volkov]], [[Albert Tumenov]], [[Rashid Magomedov]], [[Alexander Emelianenko]], [[Bazigit Atajev]], [[Magomedrasul Khasbulaev]], [[Artem Vakhitov]], [[Magomed Magomedov]], [[Mikhail Ilyukhin]], [[Shamil Zavurov]], [[Bazigit Atajev]], [[Denis Grachev (fighter)|Denis Grachev]], [[Ruslan Karaev]], [[Milana Dudieva]], [[Suleyman Magomedov]], [[Alexei Papin]], [[Aleksandr Pitchkounov]], [[Oleksiy Oliynyk]], [[Georgi Karakhanyan]], [[Andrei Semenov (fighter)|Andrei Semenov]], [[Alexander Shlemenko]], [[Akop Stepanyan]], [[Amar Suloev]], [[Alexander Yakovlev (fighter)|Alexander Yakovlev]], [[Michail Tsarev]], [[Mikhail Zayats]], [[Roman Zentsov]].\n\nOther popular martial arts form is [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]] which originated in the [[Soviet Union]].\n{{See also|Russian martial arts|Sambo (martial art)}}\n\n==Weightlifting==\n[[File:\u041d\u0430\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430_\u041c\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430,_\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435_\u043d\u0430_\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0435_\u0410\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0434_\u041a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043a.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Maryana Naumova]], the youngest Powerlifter World champion and multiple record holder]]Weightlifting is another successful sport in Russia, after the dissolution of the [[Soviet Union]], Russia ranks 16th in the all-time medal table.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} Among the most titled and popular weightlifter is [[Vasily Alekseyev]], Russia and the Soviet Union's greatest Weightlifter who set multiple World records unprecedented in his era and was a twice Olympic champion.\n\nAnother popular strongman competition in [[Russia]] is [[Powerlifting]], which is akin to a variant evolving from weightlifting. Russia is an active in the [[International Powerlifting Federation]] and one of the most successful countries along with the [[United States]], [[Poland]], [[Norway]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Taiwan]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], [[Japan]] and the [[Ukraine]]. [[Maryana Naumova]] is the youngest World champion and multiple record holders in professional powerlifting tournaments and World championships.\n\n==Wrestling==\n[[File:Alexander Karelin RN 09-2013.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The most successful wrestler of all time, and Russia's greatest wrestler, [[Alexander Karelin]]]]\n[[File:Buwaisar Saytiev.jpg|thumb|left|140px|[[Buvaisar Saitiev]], the second most decorated wrestler of all time, after Karelin]]\nThe [[Soviet Union]] was the most successful country in the history of wrestling, Russia has continued the tradition and has produced multiple Olympic and World champions. Wrestling is the most accessible and played out sport for boys and young adults in Russia especially in the Caucasus Republics and regions ([[Chechnya]], [[Dagestan]], [[Karachay-Cherkessia]], [[North-Ossetia]], [[Kabardino-Balkaria]], [[Ingushetia]]).\n\n== Fencing ==\n[[File:Stanislav Pozdnyakov 2013 Fencing WCH EFS-EQ t215754.jpg|right|110px|thumb|Pozdnyakov at the 2013 World Championships]]\nRussia has maintained a strong tradition in Fencing since Tsarist [[Russia]] where it was a popular sport amongst the Russian elites, it transitioned into the [[Soviet Union]] as a sport for the Soviet fencing enthusiasts and became a visible sport for the Soviet people which reached its peak in the 1980s in terms of success and popularity of the Sport in the [[USSR]]. After the dissolution of the [[Soviet Union]], like the former Soviet Republic of [[Ukraine]], Russia has continued the success in fencing producing multiple World and European Champions. Successful Russian fencers over the decades include: [[Viktor Sidyak]], [[Galina Gorokhova]], [[Yana Zvereva]], [[Sofiya Velikaya]], [[Aleksey Yakimenko]], [[Stanislav Pozdnyakov]], [[Valentina Rastvorova]], [[Yekaterina Dyachenko]], [[Kamil Ibragimov]], [[Pavel Kolobkov]], [[Eduard Vinokurov]], [[Karina Aznavourian]], [[Renal Ganeyev]], [[Vladimir Nazlymov]], [[Artur Akhmatkhuzin]], [[Nikolay Kovalev (fencer)|Nikolay Kovalev]], [[Inna Deriglazova]], [[Tatiana Logunova]], [[Diana Yakovleva]], [[Umyar Mavlikhanov]], [[Elena Novikova-Belova]], [[Veniamin Reshetnikov]], [[Dina Galiakbarova]], [[Timur Safin]], [[Aida Shanayeva]], [[Sergey Sharikov]], [[Yury Sisikin]], [[Yuliya Biryukova]], [[Yana Egorian]], [[Violetta Kolobova]], [[Lyubov Shutova]], [[Anna Sivkova]], [[Mark Rakita]], [[Alexandra Zabelina]], [[Aleksey Cheremisinov]].\n\n==Chess==\n{{See also|Soviet Chess School}}\n[[Chess]] is a favorite pastime, and a sport that has been dominated by Russians in the post-war (1945\u2013) era. The winner of the 1948 [[World Chess Championship]], Russian [[Mikhail Botvinnik]], started an era of Soviet dominance in the chess world. Until the end of the Soviet Union, there was only one non-Soviet champion.\n\nToday, 25 of the world's top 100 chess players are Russian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ratings.fide.com/top.phtml?list=men|title=FIDE Online. FIDE Top players \u2013 Standard Top 100 Players December 2017|first=|last=Administrator|website=Ratings.fide.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n[[File:Daniil Kvyat 2015 Malaysia.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Daniil Kvyat]]]] [[Vitaly Petrov]] became Russia's first [[Formula One]] driver in 2010. So far he has driven in F1 for three seasons with the [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] and [[Caterham F1]] teams. He scored the best result of his career when he finished third at the [[2011 Australian Grand Prix]]. [[Daniil Kvyat]] made his debut in F1 in 2014. He took his first podium finish with a second place at the [[2015 Hungarian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/content/fom-website/en/latest/headlines/2015/7/vettel-beats-kvyat-and-ricciardo-in-hungarian-thriller.html |title=Vettel beats Kvyat and Ricciardo in Hungarian thriller |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=26 July 2015 |website=Formula1.com|access-date=26 July 2015}}</ref> A [[Russian Grand Prix]] joined the calendar for the [[2014 Formula One season]], held at the [[Sochi Autodrom]]. [[Sergey Sirotkin (racing driver)|Sergey Sirotkin]] joined the F1 circuit in [[2018 Formula One season|2018]].\n\n[[Timur Timerzyanov]] has enjoyed success in [[rallycross]], winning the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]] in [[2012 European Rallycross Championship season|2012]] and [[2013 European Rallycross Championship season|2013]].\n\n[[File:GranPrixRussia2014 box.jpeg|thumb|left|280px|[[Russian Grand Prix|2014 Russia Grand Prix]] in [[Sochi]]]]Russian car manufacturer [[Lada]] (known domestically as [[AvtoVAZ]]) has competed in the [[World Touring Car Championship]], making their debut in [[2008 World Touring Car Championship season|2008]] with [[Russian Bears Motorsport]] entering [[Lada 110]]s. Lada provided factory support in [[2009 World Touring Car Championship season|2009]], with the team running three cars and upgrading to the [[Lada Priora]] during the season. The team's best performances were a pair of sixth places by [[James Thompson (racing driver)|James Thompson]] at the [[2009 FIA WTCC Race of Italy|Race of Italy]]. Lada subsequently withdrew from the championship, but they returned in [[2012 World Touring Car Championship season|2012]], entering a [[Lada Granta WTCC]] driven by Thompson at a couple of race meetings. Subsequently, they announced plans to contest a full season in [[2013 World Touring Car Championship season|2013]]. The team ran two cars in 2013, with a best result of a fifth place for Thompson in the [[2013 FIA WTCC Race of Russia|Race of Russia]], and expanded to a three car squad for [[2014 World Touring Car Championship season|2014]]. Former World Touring Car Champion [[Robert Huff]] gave Lada their first WTCC win at the 2014 Beijing round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/116177 |title=Beijing Goldenport WTCC: Rob Huff gives Lada maiden WTCC win |last1=Mills |first1=Peter |date=5 October 2014 |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Russia|Sports}}\n* [[Sport in Saint Petersburg]]\n* [[Lapta (game)]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sports governing bodies of Russia}}\n{{National sports teams of Russia}}\n{{Russia topics}}\n{{Soviet Union topics}}\n{{Sport in Asia}}\n{{Sport in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sport In Russia}}\n[[Category:Sport in Russia| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Culture of Russia}}\nThe most popular '''[[sport]]''' '''in [[Russia]]''' is [[Association Football|football]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9-FzBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT259&lpg=PT259&dq=what+is+the+most+popular+sport+in+russia+football&source=bl&ots=qh_UYRXhGV&sig=-wK3_012ZO-iNnxaSGeZbiSZvL0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSvOWJnPPMAhWGyoMKHVL0AtU4ChDoAQgsMAY|title=Lonely Planet Russia|first1=Lonely|last1=Planet|first2=Simon|last2=Richmond|first3=Marc|last3=Bennetts|first4=Marc Di|last4=Duca|first5=Anthony|last5=Haywood|first6=Anna|last6=Kaminski|first7=Tom|last7=Masters|first8=Tamara|last8=Sheward|first9=Regis St|last9=Louis|first10=Mara|last10=Vorhees|date=1 February 2015|publisher=Lonely Planet|accessdate=16 December 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> According to [[Yandex]] search analysis results rating of the most popular sports among Russians: \"[[Association Football|Football]] topped the list of the most popular sports in Russia\" with 5 to 10 million requests. [[Ice hockey]] came in second with [[handball]], [[basketball]], [[boxing]], [[auto racing]], [[volleyball]], [[Sport of athletics|athletics]], [[tennis]] and chess rounding out the top ten rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://polit.ru/news/2013/07/17/sport/|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Other popular sports include [[bandy]], [[biathlon]], [[figure skating]], [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifting]], [[gymnastics]], [[wrestling]], [[martial arts]], [[rugby union]], and [[skiing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://www.rusbandy.ru/news/7591|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Soviet Union]] (USSR) competed in the [[Olympic Games]] for the first time at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]]. Soviet and later Russian athletes never finished below fourth place in the number of gold and total medals collected at the Summer Olympics in which they competed. Russia has the most medals stripped for doping violations (51), the most of any country, four times the number of the runner-up, and nearly a third of the global total. The [[Russia at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Russian team]] was been partially banned from the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Olympics]] and [[2018 Winter Olympics]] due to the [[Doping in Russia|state-sponsored doping scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|title=With one year until 2018 Winter Games, Russia's status murky|url=http://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/18647088/with-one-year-2018-winter-games-pyeongchang-russia-status-murky-wake-doping-scandal|website=Espn.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|date=9 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-suspends-russian-noc-and-creates-a-path-for-clean-individual-athletes-to-compete-in-pyeongchang-2018-under-the-olympic-flag|title=IOC suspends Russian NOC and creates a path for clean individual athletes to compete in PyeongChang 2018 under the Olympic Flag|date=5 December 2017|website=Olympic.org|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Russian athletes were allowed to participate at the 2018 Olympics under a [[Olympic Athletes from Russia at the 2018 Winter Olympics|neutral flag]] with a name \"Olympic Athletes from Russia\".\n\n[[File:RIAN archive 833469 6th International Maxi-Marathon of Nuclear Workers.jpg|right|250px|thumb|The 6th International Maxi-Marathon of Nuclear Workers on [[Moscow]]'s central Vasilyevsky Spusk Square, 2001. Participants are workers from 14 countries having [[nuclear power]] plants in their territories.]]\n\n==Football==\n[[File:RussianBear.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Russian football fans with a gigantic \"Go Russia!\" banner, featuring the [[Russian Bear]] on the background of the [[Russian flag]]]]\n{{See also|Football in Russia|2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n\n[[association football|Football]] is the number one sport in the country.<ref name=\"Murdico2005\">{{cite book|author=Suzanne J. Murdico|title=Russia: A Primary Source Cultural Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zwEWwYhv9ZUC&pg=PT96|accessdate=19 November 2013|year=2005|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-2913-6|pages=96\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Dzhusoity | first =Afsati | last2 =Kuznetsov | first2 =Petr | title =Russian soccer loses Abramovich's funding | newspaper =Russia Beyond the Headlines | publisher =Rossiyskaya Gazeta | date =30 August 2013 | url =http://rbth.co.uk/arts/sport/2013/08/30/russian_soccer_loses_abramovichs_funding_29361.html | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Brown | first =Des | title =Russia's Soccer Relationship With England | newspaper =The Moscow Times | publisher =The Moscow Times | date =15 October 2013 | url =http://www.themoscowtimes.com/arts_n_ideas/article/russias-soccer-relationship-with-england/487832.html | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Smith | first =Chris | title =Russia \u2013 A developing football nation | work = Total Football Magazine | publisher =Total Football Magazine | url =http://www.totalfootballmag.com/features/world-football/russia-a-developing-football-nation/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> A high proportion of men are interested in it to a certain extent (and many children play it regularly) and women also join men when it comes to the national team. The Russian league has a fairly high degree of competitiveness. Many notable talented foreign players have been and are playing in the Russian league as well as local talented players worthy of a spot in the starting eleven of the best clubs.<ref>{{Citation | last =Nsehe | first =Mfonobong | title =Soccer Star Samuel Eto'o To Earn $25 Million With Russian Team | work =Forbes | publisher =Forbes.com LLC | date =12 August 2011 | url =https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2011/08/12/soccer-star-samuel-etoo-to-earn-25-million-with-russian-team/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title =Russia cracks down on hooligans | work =Fox Sports | publisher =Fox Sports Australia Pty Limited | date =22 June 2013 | url =http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/russia-cracks-down-on-hooligans/story-e6frf423-1226667892531 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Murphy | first =Chris | title =World Cup: Russian racism furore is the latest headache for FIFA | newspaper =CNN | publisher =Cable News Network | date =25 October 2013 | url =http://edition.cnn.com/2013/10/25/sport/football/football-russia-racism-2018-world-cup-fifa/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nRussia was awarded the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] on the 2nd of December 2018, hosting the tournament for the first time.<ref>{{cite news | title =World Cup 2018 host Russia has a serious soccer hooligan problem | newspaper =news.com.au | publisher =News Limited | date =31 October 2013 | url =http://www.news.com.au/world/world-cup-2018-host-russia-has-a-serious-soccer-hooligan-problem/story-fndir2ev-1226750850902 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Williams | first =Carol J. | title =Soccer World Cup 2018 host is asked to explain anti-gay law | newspaper =Los Angeles Times  | publisher =Tribune Company | date =14 August 2013 | url =http://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-soccer-2018-host-russia-gay-law-20130814,0,4543633.story#axzz2l6HVegLj | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Bird | first =Liviu | title =Russia's racism stems from lack of education but can be reversed, experts say | work =NBC Sports: ProSoccerTalk | publisher =NBC Sports | date =31 October 2013 | url =http://prosoccertalk.nbcsports.com/2013/10/31/russias-racism-stems-from-lack-of-education-but-can-be-reversed-experts-say/ | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> The event took place from 14 June to 15 July 2018, in which the [[Russia national football team|Russian team]] had its best performance since the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 tournament]], reaching the quarter-finals for the first time since the breakup of the Soviet Union, where they lost to eventual finalists [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/08/russia-world-cup-exit-proud-croatia-penalties|title=Blood, sweat and beers: Russia down but proud after World Cup exit|last=Roth|first=Andrew|date=2018-07-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n[[Beach soccer]] is a popular sport in Russia since its International Growth in the late 1990s and with the establishment of the [[FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup]] by the national teams of the member associations of [[FIFA]]. Russia is amongst the most successful and dominant country of the sport,{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} along with [[Brazil]], [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]].\n\n==Ice hockey==\n{{See also|Ice hockey in Russia|Russia men's national ice hockey team|}}\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev 20 May 2008-2.jpg|right|220px|thumb|President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] meets with the 2008 national hockey team.]]\n\nThe [[Kontinental Hockey League]] (KHL) is mostly made up of Russian teams and is widely considered the second best league in the world, after the [[NHL]]. Russian teams have won every KHL championship.\n\nRussia has won the World Championships several times:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Location !! Result\n|-\n| [[1993 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships|1993]] || [[Dortmund]] / [[Munich]], {{ih|GER}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2008 IIHF World Championship|2008]] || [[Quebec City]] / [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]], {{ih|CAN}} ||bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2009 IIHF World Championship|2009]] || [[Bern]] / [[Kloten]], {{ih|SUI}} ||bgcolor=gold| '''Gold'''\n|-\n| [[2012 IIHF World Championship|2012]] || [[Helsinki]], {{ih|FIN}} / [[Stockholm]], {{ih|SWE}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n| [[2014 IIHF World Championship|2014]] || [[Minsk]], {{ih|BLR}} || bgcolor=gold| '''Gold''' \n|-\n|}\n\n==Volleyball==\n[[File:Paris Volley - Lokomotiv Belgorod, CEV Champions League, 6 November 2014 - 04.JPG|right|210px|thumb|[[Sergey Tetyukhin]], the most successful veteran professional player, celebrated his 40th birthday in 2015, and is still a member of Russia's National team.]]\n* Gold medals (2002, 2011, 2013),5 silver medals (1993, 1998, 2000, 2007, 2010), 6 bronze medals (1997, 1997, 2001, 2006, 2008, 2009)\n\nThe [[Russia women's national volleyball team|Russian women's national volleyball team]] is ranked fifth in the [[FIVB World Rankings]].\n\nRecord for achievements of the Russian women's volleyball team:\n* 2 Olympic silver medals (2000 and 2004)\n* 2 [[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship|FIVB World Championships]] gold medals (2006 and 2010)\n* 1 [[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Champions Cup]] gold medal (1997), 1 silver medal (2001), and 1 bronze medal (1993)\n\nThe Russian volleyball junior team continue to excel, in the [[FIVB]] men ranking for junior and youth, Russia is placed first the men.\n\n==Bandy==\n[[File:2012bandy russia-sweden1.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Russia national bandy team]] in the [[Bandy World Championship 2012|World Championship 2012]]]]\nOne traditionally popular sport is [[bandy]] (informally called \"Russian hockey\"). It is considered a [[national sport]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eng.tatar-inform.ru/news/2011/01/21/33986/|title=Russian bandy players blessed for victory at world championship in Kazan|date=21 January 2011|publisher=Tatar-Inform|accessdate=31 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424230703/http://eng.tatar-inform.ru/news/2011/01/21/33986/|archivedate=24 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and is one of the biggest spectator sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://www.business-gazeta.ru/article/34748/14/&ei=pfRZT6TbIIPprAf569ijDA&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCIQ7gEwAA&prev=/search?q=%25D0%25A5%25D0%25BE%25D0%25BA%25D0%25BA%25D0%25B5%25D0%25B9+%25D1%2581+%25D0%25BC%25D1%258F%25D1%2587%25D0%25BE%25D0%25BC+%25D0%2590%25D0%25B2%25D1%2581%25D1%2582%25D1%2580%25D0%25B0%25D0%25BB%25D0%25B8%25D1%258F+%25D0%25A1%25D0%25BA%25D1%2580%25D1%258B%25D0%25BD%25D0%25BD%25D0%25B8%25D0%25BA&hl=en&biw=1024&bih=634&prmd=imvns|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> According to one survey, it is the third most popular sport in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://www.rusbandy.ru/news/7438/|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Most of the modern rules were written in England by [[Charles Goodman Tebbutt]], but the Russians claim to be the inventors of the game, and indeed there were bandy-like games played in Russia before the modern rules were standardized. When [[Federation of International Bandy]] was founded in 1955, by the [[Soviet Union]] and three Nordic countries, a common set of rules were agreed upon. Mostly the English ruled prevailed. However, one important exception was the boards from the Soviet rules.\n\nThe [[Soviet Union national bandy team|Soviet national team]] won all the [[Bandy World Championship]]s from the start 1957 until 1979. Russia is almost always one of the two best and has never missed out on a medal. The attendance has decreased in the last few years. It's still one of the biggest spectator sports though. After 10 rounds of the 2011\u20132012 [[Russian Bandy League]] the average attendance was 3,887.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://bandynet.ru/node/23247&ei=XEPhTpSGEYzMtAaihc3yAw&sa=X&oi=translate&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDIQ7gEwAA&prev=/search?q=http://bandynet.ru/node/23247&hl=en&biw=1024&bih=677&prmd=imvns|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The club with biggest public support is [[Kuzbass Kemerovo Bandy Club|HC Kuzbass]] from [[Kemerovo]]. About 26,000 watched the opening game against [[Dynamo Moscow (bandy club)|Dynamo Moscow]]. [[Yenisey Bandy Club|Yenisey]] is the current (2015) champion of the domestic league.\n\n[[Russia women's national bandy team|The national team for women]] took the silver medal in the six first [[Women's Bandy World Championship|World Championships]]. In [[2014 Women's Bandy World Championship|the 2014 WCS]], the first gold medal came.\n\nBandy is the only sport to enjoy the patronage of the [[Russian Orthodox Church]] since they're very interested in strengthening their national traditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http://bandynet.ru/v1/node/15183&sandbox=1|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBandy is a team winter sport played on ice, in which skaters use sticks to direct a ball into the opposing team's goal. The rules of the game have many similarities to those of association football. The game is played on a rectangle of ice, the same size as a football field. Each team has eleven players, one of whom is the goalkeeper. A standard bandy match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each. The offside rule is also similar to that observed in football.\n\n== Biathlon ==\n[[Biathlon]] is the most popular winter sport in Russia and ranking 1st in overall polls and TV viewership for the winter seasons. [[Russia]] has had many successful biathletes and has won Olympic and World medals. Notable biathletes include [[Vladimir Melanin]], [[Nikolay Kruglov]], [[Alexander Tikhonov]], [[Valeriy Medvedtsev]], [[Venera Chernyshova]], [[Elena Golovina]] and [[Svetlana Petcherskaia]] during the Soviet era and [[Vladimir Drachev]], [[Pavel Rostovtsev]], [[Maxim Tchoudov]], [[Viktor Maigourov]], [[Olga Zaitseva]] and [[Anton Shipulin]] in the post-communist era.\n\n==Figure skating==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin visited the Iceberg Skating Palace (2014-02-09) 04.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Russian figure skating team at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]]]] [[Figure skating]] is another popular sport; in the 1960s the Soviet Union rose to become a dominant power in figure skating, especially in pairs skating and ice dancing. At every Winter Olympics from 1964 through 2006, a Soviet or Russian pair won gold, often considered the longest winning streak in modern sports history. The streak ended in 2010 when a Chinese pair won gold in [[Figure skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Winter Olympics]], a Russian pair returned to winning gold in pairs at the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi]]. Even after the fall of the [[Soviet Union]], Russia still produced multiple Olympic and World Champions in figure skating notably [[Alexei Urmanov]], [[Ilia Kulik]], [[Alexei Yagudin]], [[Evgeni Plushenko]], [[Maria Butyrskaya]], [[Irina Slutskaya]], [[Adelina Sotnikova]], [[Yulia Lipnitskaya]], [[Maya Usova]], [[Alexander Zhulin]], [[Oksana Grishuk]], [[Evgeni Platov]], [[Anjelika Krylova]], [[Oleg Ovsyannikov]], [[Tatiana Navka]], [[Roman Kostomarov]], [[Ekaterina Gordeeva]], [[Sergei Grinkov]], [[Natalia Mishkutenok]], [[Artur Dmitriev]], [[Tatiana Totmianina]], [[Maxim Marinin]], [[Elena Berezhnaya]], [[Anton Sikhuralidze]], [[Tatiana Volosozhar]], [[Maxim Trankov]], [[Ksenia Stolbova]], [[Fedor Klimov]], [[Elena Ilinykh]], [[Nikita Katsalapov]], [[Elizaveta Tuktamysheva]], [[Evgenia Medvedeva]], [[Elena Radionova]].\n\nThe [[Russian Figure Skating Championships]] are a figure skating national championship held annually to determine the national champions of Russia. Skaters compete at the senior level in the disciplines of men's singles, women's singles, pair skating, and ice dancing.\nThe first Russian national competition was held on 5 March 1878 in St. Petersburg, Russian Empire. The winner was V. I. Sreznevski. From 1897\u2013present, official Russian national championships in figure skating were held. The first national champion of Russia in figure skating was Alexandr Nikitich Panshin, who won the Russian nationals from 1897 to 1900.\n\nBetween 1924 and 1990 Russian national championships in figure skating were not held. During this time, Russian skaters competed at the [[Soviet Figure Skating Championships]].\n\n== Speed skating ==\n\n=== Long track speed skating ===\n[[File:WSDSSC Kolomna 2016 - Pavel Kulizhnikov 2.JPG|left|thumb|300px|[[Pavel Kulizhnikov]]]]\nSpeed skating has a long tradition of excellence since the Russian Empire with [[Nikolay Strunnikov]] being one of the pioneers in speed skating, then in the [[Soviet Union]] with Speed Skating greats [[Lidiya Skoblikova]], [[Maria Isakova]], [[Valentina Stenina|the Stenins]], [[Pavel Pegov]], [[Lyudmila Titova]], [[Sergey Khlebnikov]], [[Yuri Mikhaylov]], [[Natalya Petrusyova]], [[Oleg Goncharenko]], [[Inga Artamonova]], [[Pavel Pegov]], [[Tamara Rylova]], [[Nina Statkevich]], [[Nikolay Gulyayev]], [[Igor Malkov]], [[Galina Stepanskaya]], [[Boris Shilkov]], [[Tatyana Averina]], [[Viktor Kosichkin]], [[Klara Guseva]], [[Valery Muratov]], [[Sergey Marchuk]], [[Maria Isakova]], [[Oleg Bozhev]], [[Yevgeny Grishin (speed skater)|Yevgeny Grishin]], [[Yevgeny Kulikov]]. Even after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]], the [[Russian Federation]] has maintained success in Speed Skating with [[Svetlana Bazhanova]], [[Aleksandr Golubev (speed skater)|Aleksandr Golubev]], [[Yevgeny Lalenkov]], [[Svetlana Zhurova]], [[Dmitry Lobkov]], [[Dmitry Dorofeyev]], [[Sergey Klevchenya]], [[Olga Fatkulina]], [[Ivan Skobrev]], [[Olga Graf]], [[Aleksey Yesin]]. Among the new generation of Russian talents in Speed Skating taking the World Championships and World Cup titles include [[Natalya Voronina]], [[Denis Yuskov]], [[Pavel Kulizhnikov]], [[Elizaveta Kazelina]], and [[Ruslan Murashov]].\n\n=== Short track speed skating ===\nAlthough short track is not as popular as long track in terms of results and history of winning tradition in Russia. It saw a major boost in popularity after the [[2014 Sochi Olympics]] with Korean born [[Viktor Ahn]] who competed for Russia winning three gold medals in Sochi. Other successful athletes at the Olympics and doing well in the World Championships and World Cup competitions are local born speed skaters [[Semion Elistratov]], [[Vladimir Grigorev]], [[Dmitry Migunov]], [[Sofia Prosvirnova]], [[Tatiana Borodulina]] [[Viktoriya Troytskaya]], and [[Ruslan Zakharov]].\n\n==Other winter sports==\nOther winter sports the Soviets or Russia have been strong in are [[bobsleigh]], [[Skeleton (sport)|skeleton]] and [[luge]].\n\n==Basketball==\nBasketball is a popular sport in Russia. The [[Russia national basketball team|Russian national basketball team]] is the heir of the [[Soviet Union national basketball team]] and has won several international titles.\n\nRussia is home to several internationally recognized players such as [[Andrei Kirilenko]], and 2016 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] Champion [[Timofey Mozgov]].\n\n[[PBC CSKA Moscow]] is the second most successful team in the history of European club competitions.\n\n==Rugby union==\n{{Main|Rugby union in Russia}}\n{{See also|Rugby union in the Soviet Union}}\n[[Rugby union]] is a growing sport in [[Russia]]. [[Russia national rugby union team|Russia]] is ranked 17th worldwide by the [[International Rugby Board]] (IRB),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irb.com/rankings/full.html|title=Official IRB Rankings|website=Irb.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810042746/http://www.irb.com/rankings/full.html|archivedate=10 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with over one hundred clubs and close to 20,000 players nationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irb.com/unions/union=11000087/index.html|title=Official Russia Playing Numbers|website=Irb.com|accessdate=16 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021032812/http://www.irb.com/unions/union%3D11000087/index.html|archivedate=21 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRussian domestic rugby went professional in 2005 with the launch of the [[Professional Rugby League]]. After a post-Soviet lull, Russian players are again signing with major clubs in England and France.\n\n[[Krasnoyarsk]], a large Siberian city, has traditionally been the stronghold of Russian rugby union. Domestic matches are covered in the local media, and the intra-city derby match between sides Krasny Yar and Enisei-STM can attract large crowds.\n\n[[Rugby football]] in the [[Russian Empire]] pre-dated the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|Russian Revolution]] by a number of years, but it was only played sporadically. It appears to have been the first (non-indigenous) football code to be played in Russia, around a decade before the introduction of [[association football]].<ref name=Riordan1>Riordan, James ''Sport in Soviet Society \u2014 development of sport and physical education in Russia and the USSR'' ([[Cambridge University Press]], [[Cambridge]], England, 1977) p22</ref> Mr Hopper, a Scotsman, who worked in Moscow arranged a match in the 1880s; the first football match was in 1892.<ref name=Riordan1/> In 1886, however, the Russian police clamped down on rugby because they considered it \"brutal, and liable to incite demonstrations and riots\"<ref name=Riordan1/> Condemnation by the tsar's police probably deterred many people from playing, and records of rugby over the next thirty years are sparse.\n\nRussia qualified and competed in the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] in [[New Zealand]] as Europe 2 after finishing second in the 2008\u201310 ENC. This was the team's debut in the tournament, where they faced [[Australian rugby union team|Australia]], [[Irish rugby union team|Ireland]], [[Italian rugby union team|Italy]] and the [[United States rugby union team|United States]] in Group C of the tournament. Being the second-lowest-ranked team in the tournament, Russia performed comparatively well in their opening match, running the USA close in an encounter which was lost 6\u201313. This was followed by comprehensive losses against Italy (53\u201317), Ireland (62\u201312) and Australia (68\u201322).\n\n==Rugby league==\n{{Main|Rugby league in Russia}}\n\n[[Rugby league]] is a growing sport in [[Russia]]. [[Russia national rugby league team|Russia]] is ranked 16th worldwide by the [[Rugby League International Federation]] (RLIF),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rlif.com/|title=RLIF \u2013 Rugby League International Federation|website=Rlif.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> with over 2,000 participants nationwide.\n\nRussian domestic rugby league is played at youth, student and adult levels.\n\n==Australian rules football==\nThe first Australian rules football clubs in Russia were created in May 2011, with groups starting practice matches in [[Moscow]] and [[Krasnoyarsk]] within a few weeks of each other.  Both fledgling clubs have been started by an expat Australian, but with the remainder of the playing group consisting of local Russians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20110530182212683|title=Russia's 2nd footy club springs up in a month \u2013 World Footy News|website=Worldfootynews.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20110525195432763|title=Plans in motion to create Russia's first footy club \u2013 World Footy News|website=Worldfootynews.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nRussia competed at the 2011 AFL 9s Euro Cup in Belfast, finishing in 10th place (out of 18), with wins over Catalunya and Denmark and losses to Croatia and Wales.\n\nIn 2013 there are five Australian Football clubs playing in a Moscow competition almost exclusively Russians. They are the Bees, Cherkizon, Shooters, Cosmic Pirates and Slava.\n\nIn 2015 St. Petersburg Cats team firstly took part in Gagarin Cup, ANZAC Cup and Concrete and Steel cup.\nIn 2015 May, the ANZAC Day Cup was played for the first time in Saint Petersburg at the Kolomyagi Stadium. The visiting team representing Moscow was the Lazy Koalas. The result was very lopsided, but the fact that a formal game was played outside Australia at all for such an insignificant sport was considered a success.\nScores: Lazy Koalas (Moscow) 921 defeated Saint Petersburg 13 with the game called off at halftime due to a mercy rule taking effect. \nIn 2016 Russian national team took part in AFL Europe Cup in Lisbon\n\n==Tennis==\n[[File:US Open 2012 - Sharapova 03.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Maria Sharapova]] is Russia's most successful tennis athlete. She is also the highest earning female athlete.]]\nSince the end of the Soviet era, [[tennis]] has grown in popularity and Russia has produced a number of famous tennis players. In recent years, the amount of top Russian women players has been considerable, with both [[Maria Sharapova]] and [[Dinara Safina]] reaching number one in the WTA rankings. Other Russian women to achieve international success include [[Elena Dementieva]], [[Ekaterina Makarova]], [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]], [[Anastasia Myskina]], [[Nadia Petrova]], [[Vera Zvonareva]], [[Elena Vesnina]], [[Anna Chakvetadze]], [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]] and [[Anna Kournikova]]. The Russian Federation has won the [[Fed Cup]] 4 times, in [[2004 Fed Cup|2004]], [[2005 Fed Cup|2005]], [[2007 Fed Cup|2007]] and [[2008 Fed Cup|2008]].\n\nAt the [[Tennis at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing Olympics]], Russia swept the women's tennis podium with [[Elena Dementieva]] winning the gold, [[Dinara Safina]] and [[Vera Zvonareva]] the silver and bronze, respectively. As of 16 October 2009, two Russian women were ranked in the WTA tour's top 10; with an additional two in the Top 20.\n\nRussia also boasts two former number 1 men's players\u2014Safina's older brother [[Marat Safin]] and [[Yevgeny Kafelnikov]]. Other Russian men that have made the top 50 include [[Nikolay Davydenko]], [[Igor Andreev]], [[Igor Kunitsyn]], and [[Mikhail Youzhny]]. The Russian men won the [[Davis Cup]] in [[2002 Davis Cup|2002]] and [[2006 Davis Cup|2006]].\n\nAmong Russia's new talents helping to continue the sporting tradition includes, [[Daria Kasatkina]], [[Andrey Kuznetsov (tennis)|Andrey Kuznetsov]], [[Margarita Gasparyan]], [[Andrey Rublev (tennis)|Andrey Rublev]], [[Sofya Zhuk]], and [[Roman Safiullin]].\n\n==Gymnastics==\n\n===Rhythmic gymnastics===\n[[File:Jana Kudrjavceva.jpg|thumb|left|210px|[[Yana Kudryavtseva]]]]\n[[Rhythmic gymnastics]] is considered one of the most popular sports in Russia. In addition, it is considered in general that [[Russia]] has the best rhythmic gymnasts. [[Evgenia Kanaeva]], three-time all around world champion and first and only back to back gold medallist at the olympic games, [[Yulia Barsukova]], [[Irina Tchachina]], [[Galina Beloglazova]], [[Irina Devina]], [[Tatiana Druchinina]], [[Elena Karpuchina]], [[Tatiana Kravtchenko]], [[Galima Shugurova]], [[Oxana Kostina]], [[Alina Kabaeva]], [[Natalia Lipkovskaya]], [[Daria Dmitrieva]], [[Amina Zaripova]], [[Daria Kondakova]], [[Laysan Utiasheva]], [[Zarina Gizikova]], [[Daria Shkurikhina]], [[Vera Sessina]], [[Margarita Mamun]], [[Yelena Posevina]], [[Anastasia Maksimova]], [[Olga Ilina]], [[Anna Gavrilenko]], [[Karolina Sevastyanova]], [[Anastasia Bliznyuk]], [[Alina Makarenko]], [[Ksenia Dudkina]], [[Anastasia Nazarenko]], [[Uliana Donskova]], [[Margarita Aliychuk]], [[Yanina Batyrchina]], [[Tatiana Gorbunova]], [[Maria Titova]], [[Aleksandra Soldatova]], [[Yana Kudryavtseva]], [[Daria Svatkovskaya]], [[Dina Averina]], [[Arina Averina]], [[Veronika Polyakova]], [[Yulia Bravikova]], [[Daria Dubova]], [[Sofya Skomorokh]] and [[Diana Borisova]] are amongst Russia's successful and top rhythmic gymnasts. There are many rhythmic gymnastics clubs in Russia and the most famous one is the Gazprom School which [[Irina Viner]] teaches rhythmic gymnasts in Novogorsk, Moscow, where the Russian National team is also based.\n\n=== Artistic gymnastics ===\n[[File:\u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Svetlana Khorkina]]]]Before the breakup of the [[Soviet Union]] in 1991, Soviet gymnasts dominated both men's and women's gymnastics commencing with the introduction of the full women's program into the Olympics and the overall increased standardization of the Olympic Gymnastics competition format which happened in 1952. From 1952 to 1992 inclusive, the Soviet women's squad won almost every single team title in [[World Gymnastics Championships|World Championship]] competition and at the [[Summer Olympics]]: the only four exceptions were the [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Olympics]], which they did not attend, and the 1966, 1979 and 1987 World Championships. Some of the famous Soviet gymnasts were from the [[Russian SFSR]], or of Russian origin born in the former [[Republics of the Soviet Union|SSR]].\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Soviet Union, they competed together as one nation for the last time at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] as a \"Unified Team\" winning the gold. though not as dominant as the [[Soviet Union]] and with the emergence of new countries excelling in gymnastics and having a gymnast apparatus specialist, [[Russia]] has maintained the tradition of gymnastics excellence, medalling at every Worlds and Olympic competition in both MAG and WAG disciplines, except in the [[Gymnastics at the 2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]], where the Russian women team did not win any medals. Notable Russian gymnasts include: [[Svetlana Khorkina]], [[Alexei Nemov]], [[Nikolai Andrianov]], [[Alexander Dityatin]], [[Larissa Latynina]], [[Yelena Shushunova]], [[Elena Zamolodchikova]], [[Natalia Yurchenko]], [[Elena Mukhina]], [[Olga Mostepanova]], [[Yuri Titov]], [[Anton Golotsutskov]], [[Yekaterina Lobaznyuk]], [[Yelena Produnova]], [[Natalia Shaposhnikova]], [[Ludmilla Tourischeva]], [[Anastasia Grishina]], [[Aleksandr Balandin (gymnast)|Aleksandr Balandin]], [[Maria Paseka]], [[Nikolai Kuksenkov]], [[Ksenia Afanasyeva]], [[Aliya Mustafina]], [[Denis Ablyazin]], [[Emin Garibov]], [[Viktoria Komova]], [[David Belyavskiy]], [[Nikita Nagornyy]], [[Maria Kharenkova]], [[Nikita Ignatyev]], [[Daria Spiridonova]], [[Angelina Melnikova]], [[Natalia Kapitonova]], [[Andrei Makolov]], [[Elena Eremina]] and [[Seda Tutkhalyan]].\n\n==Swimming and diving==\n[[File:Swimming pools in Russia.png|thumb|right|300px|Number of [[swimming pool]]s in Russia, 1993\u20132013]]\n[[File:Alexander Popov 006.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Alexander Popov (swimmer)|Alexander Popov]]]]\nSwimming is mostly an elite sport for most Russians, however before the dissolution of the [[USSR]], Swimming was an institutionalized and recreational sport and excelled in the Olympic Games competing against [[East Germany]] in the total swimming medals table. Russia has not achieved the same success as that of the [[Soviet Union]] nevertheless there has still been a few notable Russian swimmers that excelled, [[Alexander Popov (swimmer)|Alexander Popov]], a four-time Olympic gold medalist is regarded as one of the greatest sprint freestyle swimmers of all time,{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} and the only male swimmer in history to win four individual Olympic gold medals in freestyle events. Other Notable Russian swimmers in the 1990s and early 2000s include: [[Denis Pankratov]], [[Yevgeny Sadovyi]], [[Vladimir Pyshnenko]], [[Yury Prilukov]], [[Arkady Vyatchanin]], [[Roman Sludnov]], [[Andrey Grechin]]. After the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], Russia's new elite swimmers have shown improved results.\n\nDiving is also a sport in Russia with a long soviet tradition.\n\nRussia has dominated synchronized swimming at the Olympic Games and World Championships since the [[2000 Sydney Olympics]].{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} Notable Olympic champions and synchronized swimmers include: [[Anastasia Davydova]], [[Anastasia Ermakova]], [[Natalia Ishchenko]], [[Svetlana Romashina]], [[Darina Valitova]] and [[Aleksandr Maltsev (synchronized swimmer)|Aleksandr Maltsev]].\n\n==Athletics==\n[[File:La russe Elena Isinbaeva m\u00e9daille de bronze olympique du saut \u00e0 la perche \u00e0 Londres.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Russian Pole vaulter [[Yelena Isinbayeva]]]]Russia has maintained strong results particularly in [[High jump]], [[Long jump]], [[Track and field|track athletics]], [[Hurdling]], [[Pole vault]], [[racewalking]], [[Hammer throw]], [[Triple jump]], [[Javelin throw]], [[Heptathlon]]. Some well known Russian athletes include [[Yelena Isinbayeva]], [[Anna Chicherova]], [[Ivan Ukhov]], [[Tatyana Lysenko]], [[Yuliya Zaripova]], [[Natalya Antyukh]], [[Mikhail Ryzhov (athlete)|Mikhail Ryzhov]], [[Andrey Silnov]], [[Aleksandr Ivanov (racewalker)|Aleksandr Ivanov]], [[Ekaterina Koneva]], [[Yelena Slesarenko]], [[Sergey Shubenkov]], [[Mariya Kuchina]], [[Yuriy Borzakovskiy]], [[Darya Klishina]], [[Aleksandr Menkov]], [[Aleksey Fyodorov (athlete)|Aleksey Fyodorov]], [[Elena Lashmanova]], [[Lyukman Adams]], [[Daniil Tsyplakov]], [[Ilya Shkurenyov]].\n\nRussia was banned from the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics|2017]] and [[2019 World Championships in Athletics|2019 World Championships]] because of [[Doping in Russia|state-sponsored doping]].\n\n==Orienteering==\n{{Main|Russian Orienteering Federation}}\n\nThe '''Russian Orienteering Federation''' ([[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041e\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f (\u0424\u0421\u041e)) is the [[Russia]]n national organisation of [[orienteering]]. It is a full member of the [[International Orienteering Federation]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.orienteering.org/i3/index.php?/iof2006/iof/member_federations/iof_member_federations|title= IOF Member Federations|accessdate= 20 June 2008|work= [[International Orienteering Federation]]|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080618185711/http://www.orienteering.org/i3/index.php?%2Fiof2006%2Fiof%2Fmember_federations%2Fiof_member_federations|archivedate= 18 June 2008|url-status= dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Boxing==\n[[File:Alexander Povetkin 2015.png|thumb|right|220px|[[Alexander Povetkin]]]]\n{{See also|Russian fist fighting}}\n\nRussia is a boxing country powerhouse with many world title holders, Olympic champions and legends of the sport. Successful professional and amateur boxers include: [[Alexander Povetkin]], [[Nikolai Valuev]], [[Dmitry Bivol]], [[Eduard Troyanovsky]], [[Aleksei Tishchenko]], [[Kostya Tszyu]], [[Evgeny Tishchenko]], [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]], [[Albert Tumenov]], [[Magomed Abdusalamov]], [[Shamil Sabirov]], [[Oleg Maskaev]], [[Dmitry Kudryashov (boxer)|Dmitry Kudryashov]], [[Boris Kuznetsov (boxer)|Boris Kuznetsov]], [[Aleksandr Lebziak]], [[Sofya Ochigava]], [[Oleg Saitov]], [[Georgy Balakshin]], [[Oleg Grigoryev]], [[Vassily Solomin]], [[Nikolay Korolyov (boxer)|Nikolay Korolyov]], [[Raimkul Malakhbekov]], [[Evgeny Makarenko]], [[Alexander Maletin]], [[Alexei Lezin]], [[Gennady Kovalev]], [[Sergey Kazakov]], [[Matvey Korobov]], [[Sultan Ibragimov]], [[Artur Beterbiyev]], [[Misha Aloyan]], [[Denis Boytsov]], [[Dmitry Chudinov]], [[Fedor Chudinov]], [[Gennadiy Shatkov]], [[Grigory Drozd]], [[Egor Mekhontsev]], [[David Ayrapetyan]], [[Boris Lagutin]], [[Denis Lebedev]], [[Rashid Magomedov]], [[Ruslan Provodnikov]], [[Viktor Rybakov]], [[Vladimir Safronov]], [[Stanislav Stepashkin]], [[Valerian Sokolov]], [[Vasilii Egorov]], [[Vitaly Dunaytsev]],\n\n== Judo ==\nRussia has become a key player in sport of [[Judo]], even under the [[Soviet Union]], it has produced multiple Olympic champions and medalists. The popularity was increased under President [[Vladimir Putin]] promoting the sport, and with Russia producing multiple Olympic and World champions. Notable judokas over the decades include: [[Vladimir Nevzorov]], [[Kamal Khan-Magomedov]], [[Alexander Mikhaylin]], [[Oleg Stepanov]], [[Anatoly Laryukov]], [[Beslan Mudranov]], [[Tamerlan Tmenov]], [[Ivan Nifontov]], [[Arsen Galstyan]], [[Sergei Kosorotov]], [[Mansur Isaev]], [[Nikolai Solodukhin]], [[Elena Ivashchenko]], [[Kirill Denisov]], [[Tagir Khaybulaev]], [[Sergei Kosmynin]], [[Vitali Kuznetsov (judoka)|Vitali Kuznetsov]], [[Natalia Kuziutina]], [[Vitaliy Makarov]], [[Serhiy Novikov (judo fighter)|Serhiy Novikov]], [[Mikhail Pulyaev]], [[Dmitri Sergeyev (judoka)|Dmitri Sergeyev]], [[Yury Styopkin]],\n\n==Martial arts==\n[[File:Fedor Emelianenko 2006.jpg|thumb|left|160px| [[Fedor Emelianenko]]]][[File:Batu Khasikov 2011.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Batu Khasikov]]]]\nMixed martial arts is another popular sport producing many world class international and national fighters.\n\nNotable athletes include: [[Fedor Emelianenko]], [[Batu Khasikov]], [[Oleg Taktarov]], [[Vitaly Minakov]], [[Rasul Mirzaev]], [[Julia Berezikova]], [[Andrey Koreshkov]], [[Vyacheslav Vasilevsky]], [[Sergei Kharitonov]], [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]], [[Vladimir Mineev]], [[Muslim Salikhov]], [[Murad Machaev]], [[Viktor Nemkov]], [[Adlan Amagov]], [[Islam Makhachev]], [[Ramazan Ramazanov]], [[Zubaira Tukhugov]], [[Volk Han]], [[Omari Akhmedov]], [[Sultan Aliev]], [[Vener Galiev]], [[Ali Bagautinov]], [[Alexander Ustinov]], [[Rustam Khabilov]], [[Alexander Sarnavskiy]], [[Ruslan Magomedov]], [[Artem Levin]], [[Alexander Volkov (fighter)|Alexander Volkov]], [[Albert Tumenov]], [[Rashid Magomedov]], [[Alexander Emelianenko]], [[Bazigit Atajev]], [[Magomedrasul Khasbulaev]], [[Artem Vakhitov]], [[Magomed Magomedov]], [[Mikhail Ilyukhin]], [[Shamil Zavurov]], [[Bazigit Atajev]], [[Denis Grachev (fighter)|Denis Grachev]], [[Ruslan Karaev]], [[Milana Dudieva]], [[Suleyman Magomedov]], [[Alexei Papin]], [[Aleksandr Pitchkounov]], [[Oleksiy Oliynyk]], [[Georgi Karakhanyan]], [[Andrei Semenov (fighter)|Andrei Semenov]], [[Alexander Shlemenko]], [[Akop Stepanyan]], [[Amar Suloev]], [[Alexander Yakovlev (fighter)|Alexander Yakovlev]], [[Michail Tsarev]], [[Mikhail Zayats]], [[Roman Zentsov]].\n\nOther popular martial arts form is [[Sambo (martial art)|Sambo]] which originated in the [[Soviet Union]].\n{{See also|Russian martial arts|Sambo (martial art)}}\n\n==Weightlifting==\n[[File:\u041d\u0430\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0430_\u041c\u0430\u0440\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0430,_\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435_\u043d\u0430_\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0435_\u0410\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0434_\u041a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043a.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Maryana Naumova]], the youngest Powerlifter World champion and multiple record holder]]Weightlifting is another successful sport in Russia, after the dissolution of the [[Soviet Union]], Russia ranks 16th in the all-time medal table.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} Among the most titled and popular weightlifter is [[Vasily Alekseyev]], Russia and the Soviet Union's greatest Weightlifter who set multiple World records unprecedented in his era and was a twice Olympic champion.\n\nAnother popular strongman competition in [[Russia]] is [[Powerlifting]], which is akin to a variant evolving from weightlifting. Russia is an active in the [[International Powerlifting Federation]] and one of the most successful countries along with the [[United States]], [[Poland]], [[Norway]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Taiwan]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], [[Japan]] and the [[Ukraine]]. [[Maryana Naumova]] is the youngest World champion and multiple record holders in professional powerlifting tournaments and World championships.\n\n==Wrestling==\n[[File:Alexander Karelin RN 09-2013.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The most successful wrestler of all time, and Russia's greatest wrestler, [[Alexander Karelin]]]]\n[[File:Buwaisar Saytiev.jpg|thumb|left|140px|[[Buvaisar Saitiev]], the second most decorated wrestler of all time, after Karelin]]\nThe [[Soviet Union]] was the most successful country in the history of wrestling, Russia has continued the tradition and has produced multiple Olympic and World champions. Wrestling is the most accessible and played out sport for boys and young adults in Russia especially in the Caucasus Republics and regions ([[Chechnya]], [[Dagestan]], [[Karachay-Cherkessia]], [[North-Ossetia]], [[Kabardino-Balkaria]], [[Ingushetia]]).\n\n== Fencing ==\n[[File:Stanislav Pozdnyakov 2013 Fencing WCH EFS-EQ t215754.jpg|right|110px|thumb|Pozdnyakov at the 2013 World Championships]]\nRussia has maintained a strong tradition in Fencing since Tsarist [[Russia]] where it was a popular sport amongst the Russian elites, it transitioned into the [[Soviet Union]] as a sport for the Soviet fencing enthusiasts and became a visible sport for the Soviet people which reached its peak in the 1980s in terms of success and popularity of the Sport in the [[USSR]]. After the dissolution of the [[Soviet Union]], like the former Soviet Republic of [[Ukraine]], Russia has continued the success in fencing producing multiple World and European Champions. Successful Russian fencers over the decades include: [[Viktor Sidyak]], [[Galina Gorokhova]], [[Yana Zvereva]], [[Sofiya Velikaya]], [[Aleksey Yakimenko]], [[Stanislav Pozdnyakov]], [[Valentina Rastvorova]], [[Yekaterina Dyachenko]], [[Kamil Ibragimov]], [[Pavel Kolobkov]], [[Eduard Vinokurov]], [[Karina Aznavourian]], [[Renal Ganeyev]], [[Vladimir Nazlymov]], [[Artur Akhmatkhuzin]], [[Nikolay Kovalev (fencer)|Nikolay Kovalev]], [[Inna Deriglazova]], [[Tatiana Logunova]], [[Diana Yakovleva]], [[Umyar Mavlikhanov]], [[Elena Novikova-Belova]], [[Veniamin Reshetnikov]], [[Dina Galiakbarova]], [[Timur Safin]], [[Aida Shanayeva]], [[Sergey Sharikov]], [[Yury Sisikin]], [[Yuliya Biryukova]], [[Yana Egorian]], [[Violetta Kolobova]], [[Lyubov Shutova]], [[Anna Sivkova]], [[Mark Rakita]], [[Alexandra Zabelina]], [[Aleksey Cheremisinov]].\n\n==Chess==\n{{See also|Soviet Chess School}}\n[[Chess]] is a favorite pastime, and a sport that has been dominated by Russians in the post-war (1945\u2013) era. The winner of the 1948 [[World Chess Championship]], Russian [[Mikhail Botvinnik]], started an era of Soviet dominance in the chess world. Until the end of the Soviet Union, there was only one non-Soviet champion.\n\nToday, 25 of the world's top 100 chess players are Russian.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ratings.fide.com/top.phtml?list=men|title=FIDE Online. FIDE Top players \u2013 Standard Top 100 Players December 2017|first=|last=Administrator|website=Ratings.fide.com|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n[[File:Daniil Kvyat 2015 Malaysia.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Daniil Kvyat]]]] [[Vitaly Petrov]] became Russia's first [[Formula One]] driver in 2010. So far he has driven in F1 for three seasons with the [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] and [[Caterham F1]] teams. He scored the best result of his career when he finished third at the [[2011 Australian Grand Prix]]. [[Daniil Kvyat]] made his debut in F1 in 2014. He took his first podium finish with a second place at the [[2015 Hungarian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/content/fom-website/en/latest/headlines/2015/7/vettel-beats-kvyat-and-ricciardo-in-hungarian-thriller.html |title=Vettel beats Kvyat and Ricciardo in Hungarian thriller |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=26 July 2015 |website=Formula1.com|access-date=26 July 2015}}</ref> A [[Russian Grand Prix]] joined the calendar for the [[2014 Formula One season]], held at the [[Sochi Autodrom]]. [[Sergey Sirotkin (racing driver)|Sergey Sirotkin]] joined the F1 circuit in [[2018 Formula One season|2018]].\n\n[[Timur Timerzyanov]] has enjoyed success in [[rallycross]], winning the [[FIA European Rallycross Championship]] in [[2012 European Rallycross Championship season|2012]] and [[2013 European Rallycross Championship season|2013]].\n\n[[File:GranPrixRussia2014 box.jpeg|thumb|left|280px|[[Russian Grand Prix|2014 Russia Grand Prix]] in [[Sochi]]]]Russian car manufacturer [[Lada]] (known domestically as [[AvtoVAZ]]) has competed in the [[World Touring Car Championship]], making their debut in [[2008 World Touring Car Championship season|2008]] with [[Russian Bears Motorsport]] entering [[Lada 110]]s. Lada provided factory support in [[2009 World Touring Car Championship season|2009]], with the team running three cars and upgrading to the [[Lada Priora]] during the season. The team's best performances were a pair of sixth places by [[James Thompson (racing driver)|James Thompson]] at the [[2009 FIA WTCC Race of Italy|Race of Italy]]. Lada subsequently withdrew from the championship, but they returned in [[2012 World Touring Car Championship season|2012]], entering a [[Lada Granta WTCC]] driven by Thompson at a couple of race meetings. Subsequently, they announced plans to contest a full season in [[2013 World Touring Car Championship season|2013]]. The team ran two cars in 2013, with a best result of a fifth place for Thompson in the [[2013 FIA WTCC Race of Russia|Race of Russia]], and expanded to a three car squad for [[2014 World Touring Car Championship season|2014]]. Former World Touring Car Champion [[Robert Huff]] gave Lada their first WTCC win at the 2014 Beijing round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/116177 |title=Beijing Goldenport WTCC: Rob Huff gives Lada maiden WTCC win |last1=Mills |first1=Peter |date=5 October 2014 |website=Autosport.com |accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Russia|Sports}}\n* [[Sport in Saint Petersburg]]\n* [[Lapta (game)]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sports governing bodies of Russia}}\n{{National sports teams of Russia}}\n{{Russia topics}}\n{{Soviet Union topics}}\n{{Sport in Asia}}\n{{Sport in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sport In Russia}}\n[[Category:Sport in Russia| ]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stray word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sport_in_Russia"}
{"title_page": "Sirkazhi taluk", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Sirkazhi taluk''' is a [[taluk]] of [[Mayiladuthurai district]] of the [[Indian state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. The headquarters of the taluk is the town of [[Sirkazhi]]\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 census, the taluk of Sirkazhi had a population of 318,875 with 157,621  males and 161,254 females. There were 1023 women for every 1000 men. The taluk had a literacy rate of 73.67. Child population in the age group below 6 was 15,995 Males and 15,185 Females.<ref>{{cite web|title=Provisional Population Totals - Tamil Nadu-Census 2011|url=http://www.census.tn.nic.in/census2011data/PPT_taluk_data_final.pdf|publisher=Census Tamil Nadu|accessdate=4 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617095215/http://www.census.tn.nic.in/census2011data/PPT_taluk_data_final.pdf|archivedate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<References/>\n{{Mayiladuthurai district}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Taluks of Mayiladuthurai district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Sirkazhi taluk''' is a [[taluk]] of [[Mayiladuthurai district]] of the [[Indian state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. The headquarters of the taluk is the town of [[Sirkazhi]]\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 census, the taluk of Sirkazhi had a population of 318,875 with 157,621  males and 161,254 females. There were 1023 women for every 1000 men. The taluk had a literacy rate of 73.67. Child population in the age group below 6 was 15,995 Males and 15,185 Females.<ref>{{cite web|title=Provisional Population Totals - Tamil Nadu-Census 2011|url=http://www.census.tn.nic.in/census2011data/PPT_taluk_data_final.pdf|publisher=Census Tamil Nadu|accessdate=4 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617095215/http://www.census.tn.nic.in/census2011data/PPT_taluk_data_final.pdf|archivedate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<References/>\n{{Nagapattinam district}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Taluks of Nagapattinam district]]\n\n\n{{Nagapattinam-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shanze1", "label": "safe", "comment": "new changes post split of Mayiladuthurai dt.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sirkazhi_taluk"}
{"title_page": "Raetia football team", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name                = Raetia\n| Badge               = FAR-LOGO.png\n| Badge_size          = 200px\n| ConIFA Trigramme    = RAE\n| FIFA Rank           = \n| FIFA max            = \n| FIFA max date       = \n| FIFA min            =\n| FIFA min date       = \n| Elo Rank            = \n| Elo max             =\n| Elo max date        = \n| Elo min             = \n| Elo min date        = \n| Elo rating max      =\n| Elo rating max date = \n| Nickname            =  ''[[Three Leagues|The Grisons]]''\n| Association         = Raetia Football Association<br /> (Fussballauswahl Raetia)\n| Confederation       = [[ConIFA]] \n| Coach               = Aziz Agirman\n| Captain             = Serkan Karamese\n| Vice Captain        =\n| Most caps           = \n| Top scorer          = \n| Ballon d'Or Winners = \n| Home Stadium        = \n<!--Home Shirt-->\n| pattern_la1=|pattern_b1=|pattern_ra1=\n| leftarm1=ffffff|body1=ffffff|rightarm1=ffffff|shorts1=000000|socks1=000000\n<!--Away Shirt-->\n| pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_ra2=\n| leftarm2=0000ff|body2=0000ff|rightarm2=0000ff|shorts2=000000|socks2=000000\n<!--End of Shirt-->\n| First game = {{fb|Chagos Islands}} 6\u20131 {{fb-rt|Raetia}}<br />\n([[Crawley]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]; 4 December 2011)\n| Largest win = \n{{fb|Raetia}} 6\u20130 {{fb-rt|Franconia}} <br />\n([[Chur]], [[Switzerland]]; 5 September 2015)\n\n| Largest loss = {{fb|Gozo}} 17\u20131 {{fb-rt|Raetia}} <br />\n([[Xewkija]], [[Malta]]; 14 January 2012)\n| Honours = \n| Regional name = \n| Regional cup apps = \n| Regional cup first = \n| Regional cup best = \n|2ndRegional name         = \n|2ndRegional cup apps     = \n|2ndRegional cup first    =\n|2ndRegional cup best     = \n| Confederations cup apps = \n| Confederations cup first = \n| Confederations cup best = \n| medaltemplates =\n}}\n\nThe '''Raetia football team''' ({{lang-de|Fussballauswahl Raetia}}) represents [[Raetia]] in [[ConIFA]] [[association football]]. The current head coach is Pascal Amrein. The team is commonly referred to as ''[[Three Leagues|The Grisons]]''.<ref>http://www.punktmagazin.ch/tag/fa-raetia/</ref>\n\n==History==\nRaetia's first game was played in December 2011 against the [[Chagos Islands national football team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chagossupport.org.uk/chagos-footballers-to-play-swiss-team-in-friendly-match-1863 |title=Chagos footballers to play Swiss team in friendly match |publisher=Chagossupport.org.uk |date=2011-11-28 |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suedostschweiz.ch/vermischtes/fa-ratia-verliert-ohne-gimma |title=Vermischtes: FA R\u00e4tia verliert ohne Gimma |publisher=Suedostschweiz.ch |date= |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> The second game took place in January 2012 on the island of Gozo against Gozo.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gfa.com.mt/Match_Report_Gozo_Vs_FCRatia_part_1.html |title=Gozo Vs FA Ratia |publisher=Gfa.com.mt |accessdate=2012-08-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224055558/http://www.gfa.com.mt/Match_Report_Gozo_Vs_FCRatia_part_1.html |archivedate=24 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://footy-fever.com/blog/2013-african-cup-of-nations-qualifiers-stps-mystery-surprise/ |title=2013 African Cup of Nations Qualifiers: STP\u2019s Mystery & Surprise |publisher=Footy-fever.com |accessdate=2012-08-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502163323/http://footy-fever.com/blog/2013-african-cup-of-nations-qualifiers-stps-mystery-surprise/ |archivedate=2 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe first home game was on 26 May 2012 against the fifth Team of FC St. Pauli in [[Domat/Ems]] and Raetia won 6\u20130.\n\nRaetia was qualified to play the [[2012 VIVA World Cup]] in the northern Iraqi region of Kurdistan. In the group matches they gained a victory against Tamil Eelam and a loss to Zanzibar the 2nd rank and missed the semi-finals only because of goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20min.ch/sport/fussball/story/27197631 |title=20 Minuten Online - \"Das Swat-Team auf der Trib\u00fcne war belustigend\" - Fussball |publisher=20min.ch |date= |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.20min.ch/sport/fussball/story/22206569 |title=20 Minuten Online - Schweizer Kicker k\u00e4mpften im Irak - Fussball |publisher=20min.ch |date= |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 September 2015 Raetia beat [[Franconia]] 6\u20130 and qualified for the [[2016 ConIFA World Football Cup]] in Abkhazia.\n\n==National Anthem==\nThe National Anthem of Raetia is \"A Tgalaveina\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ingeb.org/Lieder/udisilcl.html |title=A Tgalaveina / Udis il clom en la vallada free midi mp3 download Strand Hotel Sechelt bed breakfast |publisher=Ingeb.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>\n\nUdis il clom en la vallada? <br />\nSi, si vus umens dils cumins! <br />\nLa libertad el smanatschada, <br />\nIgl inimitg ei sils confins. <br />\n<br />\nRefrain: <br />\nFontana muoss'a nus la via atras<br />\nIls flugs //dils battagliuns//.<br />\nPlitost la mort che sclaveria<br />\nEi la parola dils Grischuns.\n\n==Players & Manager==\n\n===Manager===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nationality\n! Name\n|-\n| 2011\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}}\n|Rudolf Schmid\n|-\n| 2011\u20132012\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}}\n|Gian-Marco Schmid\n|-\n| 2012\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}}\n|Ursin Caviezel\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}}\n| Costatino Demenga\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}} {{Flag icon|Kosovo}}\n| Arsim Ramizi\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}} {{Flag icon|CRO}}\n| Alen Bratelj\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}}\n| Pascal Amrein\n|-\n| 2017\u2013present\n| {{Flag icon|SUI}} \n| Aziz Agirman\n|}\n\n==Competitive record==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break|width=40%}}\n\n===VIVA World Cup===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[VIVA World Cup|VIVA World Cup Record]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!GP\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!GS\n!GA\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Occitania}} 2006\n|rowspan=4 colspan=8|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|S\u00e1pmi}} 2008\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Padania}} 2009\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Gozo}} 2010\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Kurdistan}} [[2012 VIVA World Cup|2012]]||Round of 8||8th||4||1||0||3||1||13\n|}\n\n===ConIFA World Football Cup===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=9|[[ConIFA World Football Cup|ConIFA World Football Cup Record]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!GP\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!GS\n!GA\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Sapmi}} 2014\n|rowspan=1 colspan=8|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Abkhazia}} 2016||Round of 12||11th||4||0||1||3||3||23\n|-\n|{{flagicon|Barawa}} 2018\n|rowspan=1 colspan=8|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n|}\n\n===EUROPEADA European Championship===\n\n2008, 2010 and 2012 was not the Raetian national team at the tournament but a selection of the <br/>rhaeto-romance speaking part of the canton of Grisons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liarumantscha.ch/sites/home/news.html?news:view=details_video&id=282&lang2=de |title=R\u00e4toromanische Mannschaft an der Europeada 2012 |publisher=Liarumantscha.ch |date= |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n\n===All time results and upcoming fixtures===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Place\n!Home\n!Guest\n!Score\n|-\n|23 March 2019|| {{ITA|#}}, [[Rome]] || {{fb|Vatican City}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 2\u20132\n|-\n|12 March 2017|| {{SUI|#}}, [[Trubbach]] || {{fb|Raetia}} || {{fb|Tamil Eelam}} || 0\u20135\n|-\n|3 June 2016|| {{flag|Abkhazia}}, [[Gagra]] || {{fb|Chagos Islands}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 3\u20134 \n|-\n|2 June 2016|| {{flag|Abkhazia}}, [[Gagra]] || {{fb|Sz\u00e9kely Land}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 7\u20130\n|-\n|31 May 2016|| {{flag|Abkhazia}}, [[Gagra]] || {{fb|Northern Cyprus}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 7\u20130\n|-\n|30 May 2016|| {{flag|Abkhazia}}, [[Gagra]] || {{fb|Raetia}} || {{fb|Padania}} || 0\u20136\n|-\n|6 September 2015|| {{SUI|#}}, [[Chur]] || {{fb|Raetia}} || {{fb|Franconia}} || 6\u20130\n|-\n|8 November 2014|| {{ROM|#}}, [[Sepsiszentgy\u00f6rgy]] || {{fb|Sz\u00e9kely Land}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 3\u20130\n|-\n|9 August 2014|| {{SUI|#}}, [[Chur]] || {{fb|Raetia}} || {{fb|Sealand}} || 1\u20136\n|-\n|29 May 2014|| {{GER|#}}, [[Lohr am Main]] || {{fb|Franconia}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 4\u20132\n|-\n|7 July 2013|| {{IOM|#}}, [[St John's, Isle of Man|St John's]] || {{fb|Tamil Eelam}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 5\u20130\n|-\n|6 July 2013|| {{IOM|#}}, [[St John's, Isle of Man|St John's]] || {{fb|Raetia}} || {{fb|Alderney}} || 3\u20132\n|-\n|29 June 2013|| {{FRA|#}}, [[La Chaux (Doubs)|La Chaux]] || {{fb|Saugeais}} || {{fb|Raetia}} ||1\u20131\n|-\n|10 June 2012|| {{FRA|#}}, [[Beausoleil, Alpes-Maritimes|Beausoleil]] || {{fb|Monaco}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 1\u20132\n|-\n|9 June 2012|| {{IRQ|#}}, [[Arbil]] || {{fb|Tamil Eelam}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 4\u20130\n|-\n|8 June 2012|| {{IRQ|#}}, [[Arbil]] || {{fb|Western Sahara}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 3\u20130\n|-\n|5 June 2012|| {{IRQ|#}}, [[Arbil]] || {{fb|Tamil Eelam}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 0\u20131\n|-\n|4 June 2012|| {{IRQ|#}}, [[Arbil]] || {{fb|Zanzibar}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 6\u20130\n|-\n|14 January 2012|| {{MLT|#}}, [[Xewkija]] || {{fb|Gozo}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 17\u20131\n|-\n|4 December 2011|| {{GBR|#}}, [[Crawley]] || {{fb|Chagos Islands}} || {{fb|Raetia}} || 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==Home stadium==\nRaetia does not have a national stadium as such, though major matches are usually played in Chur, Ems or Trin.<br/> Other large grounds which could be used include Vaduz and Bellinzona.\n\n==Colours==\nRaetia's traditional kit is a white jersey with black, accompanied by black shorts and socks while their current away kit<br/> is a royal blue shirt. As a reference to the 60th jubilee of Queen Elizabeth, Raetia has worn the blue shirts on 9 June 2012<br/> against Tamil Eelam.\n\nThe colours blue-white-grey/black are the [[national colours]] of Raetia.\n\n==